icmpV4MessagesReceivedErrors.description: Messages Received Errors is the number of ICMP messages that the entity received but determined as having errors (bad ICMP checksums, bad length, etc)..

icmpV4MessagesReceivedPerSec.name: icmpV4MessagesReceivedPerSec
icmpV4MessagesReceivedPerSec.description: Messages Received/sec is the rate at which ICMP messages are received by the entity. The rate includes those messages received in error.

icmpV4MessagesSentPerSec.name: icmpV4MessagesSentPerSec
icmpV4MessagesSentPerSec.description: Messages Sent/sec is the rate at which ICMP messages are attempted to be sent by the entity. The rate includes those messages sent in error.

icmpV4MessagesPerSec.name: icmpV4MessagesPerSec
icmpV4MessagesPerSec.description: Messages/sec is the total rate at which ICMP messages are sent and received by the entity. The rate includes those messages received or sent in error.

icmpV4RcvdAddressMask.name: icmpV4RcvdAddressMask
icmpV4RcvdAddressMask.description: Received Address Mask is the number of ICMP Address Mask Request messages received.

icmpV4RcvdAddressMaskReply.name: icmpV4RcvdAddressMaskReply
icmpV4RcvdAddressMaskReply.description: Received Address Mask Reply is the number of ICMP Address Mask Reply messages received.

icmpV4RcvdDestUnreachable.name: icmpV4RcvdDestUnreachable
icmpV4RcvdDestUnreachable.description: Received Destination Unreachable is the number of ICMP Destination Unreachable messages received.

icmpV4RcvdEchoReplyPerSec.name: icmpV4RcvdEchoReplyPerSec
icmpV4RcvdEchoReplyPerSec.description: Received Echo Reply/sec is the rate of ICMP Echo Reply messages received.

icmpV4RcvdEchoPerSec.name: icmpV4RcvdEchoPerSec
icmpV4RcvdEchoPerSec.description: Received Echo/sec is the rate of ICMP Echo messages received.

icmpV4RcvdParameterProblem.name: icmpV4RcvdParameterProblem
icmpV4RcvdParameterProblem.description: Received Parameter Problem is the number of ICMP Parameter Problem messages received.

icmpV4RcvdRedirectPerSec.name: icmpV4RcvdRedirectPerSec
icmpV4RcvdRedirectPerSec.description: Received Redirect/sec is the rate of ICMP Redirect messages received.

icmpV4RcvdSourceQuench.name: icmpV4RcvdSourceQuench
icmpV4RcvdSourceQuench.description: Received Source Quench is the number of ICMP Source Quench messages received.

icmpV4RcvdTimeExceeded.name: icmpV4RcvdTimeExceeded
icmpV4RcvdTimeExceeded.description: Received Time Exceeded is the number of ICMP Time Exceeded messages received.

icmpV4RcvdTimestampReplyPerSec.name: icmpV4RcvdTimestampReplyPerSec
icmpV4RcvdTimestampReplyPerSec.description: Received Timestamp Reply/sec is the rate of ICMP Timestamp Reply messages received.

icmpV4RcvdTimestampPerSec.name: icmpV4RcvdTimestampPerSec
icmpV4RcvdTimestampPerSec.description: Received Timestamp/sec is the rate of ICMP Timestamp (request) messages received.

icmpV4SentAddressMask.name: icmpV4SentAddressMask
icmpV4SentAddressMask.description: Sent Address Mask is the number of ICMP Address Mask Request messages sent.

icmpV4SentAddressMaskReply.name: icmpV4SentAddressMaskReply
icmpV4SentAddressMaskReply.description: Sent Address Mask Reply is the number of ICMP Address Mask Reply messages sent.

icmpV4SentDestinationUnreachable.name: icmpV4SentDestinationUnreachable
icmpV4SentDestinationUnreachable.description: Sent Destination Unreachable is the number of ICMP Destination Unreachable messages sent.

icmpV4SentEchoReplyPerSec.name: icmpV4SentEchoReplyPerSec
icmpV4SentEchoReplyPerSec.description: Sent Echo Reply/sec is the rate of ICMP Echo Reply messages sent.

icmpV4SentEchoPerSec.name: icmpV4SentEchoPerSec
icmpV4SentEchoPerSec.description: Sent Echo/sec is the rate of ICMP Echo messages sent.

icmpV4SentParameterProblem.name: icmpV4SentParameterProblem
icmpV4SentParameterProblem.description: Sent Parameter Problem is the number of ICMP Parameter Problem messages sent.

icmpV4SentRedirectPerSec.name: icmpV4SentRedirectPerSec
icmpV4SentRedirectPerSec.description: Sent Redirect/sec is the rate of ICMP Redirect messages sent.

icmpV4SentSourceQuench.name: icmpV4SentSourceQuench
icmpV4SentSourceQuench.description: Sent Source Quench is the number of ICMP Source Quench messages sent.

icmpV4SentTimeExceeded.name: icmpV4SentTimeExceeded
icmpV4SentTimeExceeded.description: Sent Time Exceeded is the number of ICMP Time Exceeded messages sent.

icmpV4SentTimestampReplyPerSec.name: icmpV4SentTimestampReplyPerSec
icmpV4SentTimestampReplyPerSec.description: Sent Timestamp Reply/sec is the rate of ICMP Timestamp Reply messages sent.

icmpV4SentTimestampPerSec.name: icmpV4SentTimestampPerSec
icmpV4SentTimestampPerSec.description: Sent Timestamp/sec is the rate of ICMP Timestamp (request) messages sent.

icmpV6MessagesOutboundErrors.name: icmpV6MessagesOutboundErrors
icmpV6MessagesOutboundErrors.description: Messages Outbound Errors is the number of ICMP messages that were not send due to problems within ICMP, such as lack of buffers. This value does not include errors discovered outside the ICMP layer, such as those recording the failure of IP to route the resultant datagram. In some implementations, none of the error types are included in the value of this counter.

icmpV6MessagesReceivedErrors.name: icmpV6MessagesReceivedErrors
icmpV6MessagesReceivedErrors.description: Messages Received Errors is the number of ICMP messages that the entity received but had errors, such as bad ICMP checksums, bad length, etc.

icmpV6MessagesReceivedPerSec.name: icmpV6MessagesReceivedPerSec
icmpV6MessagesReceivedPerSec.description: Messages Received/sec is the rate, in incidents per second at which ICMP messages were received. The rate includes messages received in error.

icmpV6MessagesSentPerSec.name: icmpV6MessagesSentPerSec
icmpV6MessagesSentPerSec.description: Messages Sent/sec is the rate, in incidents per second, at which the server attempted to send. The rate includes those messages sent in error.

icmpV6MessagesPerSec.name: icmpV6MessagesPerSec
icmpV6MessagesPerSec.description: Messages/sec is the total rate, in incidents per second, at which ICMP messages were sent and received by the entity. The rate includes messages received or sent in error.

icmpV6ReceivedDestUnreachable.name: icmpV6ReceivedDestUnreachable
icmpV6ReceivedDestUnreachable.description: Received Destination Unreachable is the number of ICMP Destination Unreachable messages received.

icmpV6ReceivedEchoReplyPerSec.name: icmpV6ReceivedEchoReplyPerSec
icmpV6ReceivedEchoReplyPerSec.description: Received Echo Reply/sec is the rate, in incidents per second, at which ICMP Echo Reply messages were received.

icmpV6ReceivedEchoPerSec.name: icmpV6ReceivedEchoPerSec
icmpV6ReceivedEchoPerSec.description: Received Echo/sec is the rate, in incidents per second, at which ICMP Echo messages were received.

icmpV6ReceivedMembershipQuery.name: icmpV6ReceivedMembershipQuery
icmpV6ReceivedMembershipQuery.description: Received Membership Query is the number of packets received thatquery their membership to a group.

icmpV6ReceivedMembershipReduct.name: icmpV6ReceivedMembershipReduct
icmpV6ReceivedMembershipReduct.description: Received Membership Reduction is the number of packets received thatcancelled their membership to a group.

icmpV6ReceivedMembershipReport.name: icmpV6ReceivedMembershipReport
icmpV6ReceivedMembershipReport.description: Received Membership Report is the number of packets received thatreport their membership to a group.

icmpV6ReceivedNeighborAdvert.name: icmpV6ReceivedNeighborAdvert
icmpV6ReceivedNeighborAdvert.description: Received Neighbor Advert is the number of packets received thatadvert a neighbor.

icmpV6ReceivedNeighborSolicit.name: icmpV6ReceivedNeighborSolicit
icmpV6ReceivedNeighborSolicit.description: Received Neighbor Solicit is the number of packets received thatsolicit a neighbor.

icmpV6ReceivedPacketTooBig.name: icmpV6ReceivedPacketTooBig
icmpV6ReceivedPacketTooBig.description: Received Packet Too Big is the number of received packets thatare larger than anticipated.

icmpV6ReceivedParameterProblem.name: icmpV6ReceivedParameterProblem
icmpV6ReceivedParameterProblem.description: Received Parameter Problem is the number of ICMP Parameter Problem messages received.

icmpV6ReceivedRedirectPerSec.name: icmpV6ReceivedRedirectPerSec
icmpV6ReceivedRedirectPerSec.description: Received Redirect/sec is the rate, in incidents per second, at which ICMP Redirect messages were received.

icmpV6ReceivedRouterAdvert.name: icmpV6ReceivedRouterAdvert
icmpV6ReceivedRouterAdvert.description: Received Router Advert is the number of packets received thatadvert the router.

icmpV6ReceivedRouterSolicit.name: icmpV6ReceivedRouterSolicit
icmpV6ReceivedRouterSolicit.description: Received Router Solicit is the number of packets received thatsolicit the router.

icmpV6ReceivedTimeExceeded.name: icmpV6ReceivedTimeExceeded
icmpV6ReceivedTimeExceeded.description: Received Time Exceeded is the number of ICMP Time Exceeded messages received.

icmpV6SentDestinationUnreachable.name: icmpV6SentDestinationUnreachable
icmpV6SentDestinationUnreachable.description: Sent Destination Unreachable is the number of ICMP Destination Unreachable messages sent.

icmpV6SentEchoReplyPerSec.name: icmpV6SentEchoReplyPerSec
icmpV6SentEchoReplyPerSec.description: Sent Echo Reply/sec is the rate, in incidents per second, at which ICMP Echo Reply messages were sent.

icmpV6SentEchoPerSec.name: icmpV6SentEchoPerSec
icmpV6SentEchoPerSec.description: Sent Echo/sec is the rate of ICMP Echo messages sent.

icmpV6SentMembershipQuery.name: icmpV6SentMembershipQuery
icmpV6SentMembershipQuery.description: Sent Membership Query is the number of packets sent thatquery their membership to a group.

icmpV6SentMembershipReduction.name: icmpV6SentMembershipReduction
icmpV6SentMembershipReduction.description: Sent Membership Reduction is the number of packets sent thatcancelled their membership to a group.

icmpV6SentMembershipReport.name: icmpV6SentMembershipReport
icmpV6SentMembershipReport.description: Sent Membership Report is the number of packets sent thatreport their membership to a group.

icmpV6SentNeighborAdvert.name: icmpV6SentNeighborAdvert
icmpV6SentNeighborAdvert.description: Sent Neighbor Advert is the number of packets sent thatadvert a neighbor.

icmpV6SentNeighborSolicit.name: icmpV6SentNeighborSolicit
icmpV6SentNeighborSolicit.description: Sent Neighbor Solicit is the number of packets sent thatsolicit a neighbor.

icmpV6SentPacketTooBig.name: icmpV6SentPacketTooBig
icmpV6SentPacketTooBig.description: Sent Packet Too Big is the number of sent packets thatare larger than anticipated.

icmpV6SentParameterProblem.name: icmpV6SentParameterProblem
icmpV6SentParameterProblem.description: Sent Parameter Problem is the number of ICMP Parameter Problem messages sent.

icmpV6SentRedirectPerSec.name: icmpV6SentRedirectPerSec
icmpV6SentRedirectPerSec.description: Sent Redirect/sec is the rate, in incidents per second, at which ICMP Redirect messages were sent.

icmpV6SentRouterAdvert.name: icmpV6SentRouterAdvert
icmpV6SentRouterAdvert.description: Sent Router Advert is the number of packets sent thatadvert the router.

icmpV6SentRouterSolicit.name: icmpV6SentRouterSolicit
icmpV6SentRouterSolicit.description: Sent Router Solicit is the number of packets sent thatsolicit the router.

icmpV6SentTimeExceeded.name: icmpV6SentTimeExceeded
icmpV6SentTimeExceeded.description: Sent Time Exceeded is the number of ICMP Time Exceeded messages sent.

indexingServiceTable.name: indexingServiceTable
indexingServiceTable.description: The Indexing Service performance object counters report statistics pertaining to the creation of indexes and the merging and querying of indexes by Indexing Service.

indexingServiceEntry.name: indexingServiceEntry
indexingServiceEntry.description: Performance information for one particular instance of 'Indexing Service' object.

idxSvcNumDocumentsIndexed.name: idxSvcNumDocumentsIndexed
idxSvcNumDocumentsIndexed.description: Number of documents indexed since the index was mounted.

idxSvcDeferredForIndexing.name: idxSvcDeferredForIndexing
idxSvcDeferredForIndexing.description: Number of files not available and deferred for indexing.

idxSvcFilesToBeIndexed.name: idxSvcFilesToBeIndexed
idxSvcFilesToBeIndexed.description: Number of files to be filtered and added to the index.

idxSvcIndexSizeMB.name: idxSvcIndexSizeMB
idxSvcIndexSizeMB.description: Size of the content index (*.ci files only) in megabytes.

idxSvcMergeProgress.name: idxSvcMergeProgress
idxSvcMergeProgress.description: Percent merge complete for the current merge.

idxSvcRunningQueries.name: idxSvcRunningQueries
idxSvcRunningQueries.description: Number of active query client connections.

idxSvcTotalNumDocuments.name: idxSvcTotalNumDocuments
idxSvcTotalNumDocuments.description: Total number of documents in the index.

idxSvcTotalNumOfQueries.name: idxSvcTotalNumOfQueries
idxSvcTotalNumOfQueries.description: Total number of queries since the index was mounted.

idxSvcUniqueKeys.name: idxSvcUniqueKeys
idxSvcUniqueKeys.description: Number of unique keys (words, etc.) in the index.

indexingServiceFilterTable.name: indexingServiceFilterTable
indexingServiceFilterTable.description: The Index Service Filter object monitors the filtering activity of Indexing Service.

indexingServiceFilterEntry.name: indexingServiceFilterEntry
indexingServiceFilterEntry.description: Performance information for one particular instance of 'Indexing Service Filter' object.

idxSvcFilterBindingTimeMsec.name: idxSvcFilterBindingTimeMsec
idxSvcFilterBindingTimeMsec.description: Average time spent binding to indexing filters.

idxSvcFilterIdxSpeedMBPerHr.name: idxSvcFilterIdxSpeedMBPerHr
idxSvcFilterIdxSpeedMBPerHr.description: Speed of indexing contents of files in megabytes per hour.

idxSvcFilterTotalIdxSpeedMBPerHr.name: idxSvcFilterTotalIdxSpeedMBPerHr
idxSvcFilterTotalIdxSpeedMBPerHr.description: Speed of indexing file contents and properties in megabytes per hour.

internetInformationServicesGlobal.name: internetInformationServicesGlobal
internetInformationServicesGlobal.description: The Internet Information Services Global performance object consists of counters that apply jointly to the Hypertext Transport Protocol (HTTP) service and File Transfer Protocol (FTP) service.

iisGlobalActiveFlushedEntries.name: iisGlobalActiveFlushedEntries
iisGlobalActiveFlushedEntries.description: Active Flushed Entries are cached file handles that will be closed when all current transfers complete.

iisGlobalBLOBCacheFlushes.name: iisGlobalBLOBCacheFlushes
iisGlobalBLOBCacheFlushes.description: BLOB Cache Flushes since server startup.

iisGlobalBLOBCacheHits.name: iisGlobalBLOBCacheHits
iisGlobalBLOBCacheHits.description: Total number of successful lookups in the BLOB cache.

iisGlobalBLOBCacheHitsPercent.name: iisGlobalBLOBCacheHitsPercent
iisGlobalBLOBCacheHitsPercent.description: The ratio of BLOB Cache Hits to total cache requests.

iisGlobalBLOBCacheMisses.name: iisGlobalBLOBCacheMisses
iisGlobalBLOBCacheMisses.description: Total number of unsuccessful lookups in the BLOB cache.

iisGlobalCurBLOBsCached.name: iisGlobalCurBLOBsCached
iisGlobalCurBLOBsCached.description: BLOB information blocks currently in the cache for WWW and FTP services.

iisGlobalCurBlockAsyncIORequests.name: iisGlobalCurBlockAsyncIORequests
iisGlobalCurBlockAsyncIORequests.description: Current requests temporarily blocked due to bandwidth throttling settings.

iisGlobalCurFileCacheMemUsage.name: iisGlobalCurFileCacheMemUsage
iisGlobalCurFileCacheMemUsage.description: Current number of bytes used for file cache.

iisGlobalCurFilesCached.name: iisGlobalCurFilesCached
iisGlobalCurFilesCached.description: Current number of files whose content is in the cache for WWW and FTP services.

iisGlobalCurURIsCached.name: iisGlobalCurURIsCached
iisGlobalCurURIsCached.description: URI information blocks currently in the cache for WWW and FTP services.

iisGlobalFileCacheFlushes.name: iisGlobalFileCacheFlushes
iisGlobalFileCacheFlushes.description: File Cache Flushes since server startup.

iisGlobalFileCacheHits.name: iisGlobalFileCacheHits
iisGlobalFileCacheHits.description: Total number of successful lookups in the file cache.

iisGlobalFileCacheHitsPercent.name: iisGlobalFileCacheHitsPercent
iisGlobalFileCacheHitsPercent.description: The ratio of File Cache Hits to total cache requests.

iisGlobalFileCacheMisses.name: iisGlobalFileCacheMisses
iisGlobalFileCacheMisses.description: Total number of unsuccessful lookups in the file cache.

iisGlobalMaxFileCacheMemUsage.name: iisGlobalMaxFileCacheMemUsage
iisGlobalMaxFileCacheMemUsage.description: Maximum number of bytes used for file cache.

iisGlobalMeasuredAsyncIOBwUsage.name: iisGlobalMeasuredAsyncIOBwUsage
iisGlobalMeasuredAsyncIOBwUsage.description: Measured bandwidth of asynchronous I/O averaged over a minute.

iisGlobalTotalAllowedAsyncIOReqs.name: iisGlobalTotalAllowedAsyncIOReqs
iisGlobalTotalAllowedAsyncIOReqs.description: Total requests allowed by bandwidth throttling settings (counted since service startup).

iisGlobalTotalBLOBsCached.name: iisGlobalTotalBLOBsCached
iisGlobalTotalBLOBsCached.description: Total number of BLOB information blocks ever added to the cache for WWW and FTP services

iisGlobalTotalBlockAsyncIOReqs.name: iisGlobalTotalBlockAsyncIOReqs
iisGlobalTotalBlockAsyncIOReqs.description: Total requests temporarily blocked due to bandwidth throttling settings (counted since service startup).

iisGlobalTotalFilesCached.name: iisGlobalTotalFilesCached
iisGlobalTotalFilesCached.description: Total number of files whose content was ever added to the cache for WWW and FTP services

iisGlobalTotalFlushedBLOBs.name: iisGlobalTotalFlushedBLOBs
iisGlobalTotalFlushedBLOBs.description: Total Flushed BLOBs is the number of BLOB information blocks that have been removed from the cache since service start up.

iisGlobalTotalFlushedFiles.name: iisGlobalTotalFlushedFiles
iisGlobalTotalFlushedFiles.description: Total Flushed Files is the number of file handles that have been removed from the cache since service start up.

iisGlobalTotalFlushedURIs.name: iisGlobalTotalFlushedURIs
iisGlobalTotalFlushedURIs.description: Total Flushed URIs is the number of URI information blocks that have been removed from the cache since service start up.

iisGlobalTotalRejectedAsyncIOReq.name: iisGlobalTotalRejectedAsyncIOReq
iisGlobalTotalRejectedAsyncIOReq.description: Total requests rejected due to bandwidth throttling settings (counted since service startup).

iisGlobalTotalURIsCached.name: iisGlobalTotalURIsCached
iisGlobalTotalURIsCached.description: Total number of URI information blocks ever added to the cache for WWW and FTP services

iisGlobalURICacheFlushes.name: iisGlobalURICacheFlushes
iisGlobalURICacheFlushes.description: URI Cache Flushes since server startup.

iisGlobalURICacheHits.name: iisGlobalURICacheHits
iisGlobalURICacheHits.description: Total number of successful lookups in the URI cache.

iisGlobalURICacheHitsPercent.name: iisGlobalURICacheHitsPercent
iisGlobalURICacheHitsPercent.description: The ratio of URI Cache Hits to total cache requests.

iisGlobalURICacheMisses.name: iisGlobalURICacheMisses
iisGlobalURICacheMisses.description: Total number of unsuccessful lookups in the URI cache.

ipV4.name: ipV4
ipV4.description: The Internet Protocol (IP) performance object includes counters that describe the rates at which IP datagrams are transmitted by a computer using the IP protocol. It also describes various error counts for the IP protocol.

ipV4DatagramsForwardedPerSec.name: ipV4DatagramsForwardedPerSec
ipV4DatagramsForwardedPerSec.description: Datagrams Forwarded/sec is the rate, in incidents per second, at which attemps were made to find routes to forward input datagrams their final destination, because the local server was not the final IP destination. In servers that do not act as IP Gateways, this rate includes only packets that were source-routed via this entity, where the source-route option processing was successful.

ipV4DatagramsOutboundDiscarded.name: ipV4DatagramsOutboundDiscarded
ipV4DatagramsOutboundDiscarded.description: Datagrams Outbound Discarded is the number of output IP datagrams that were discarded even though no problems were encountered to prevent their transmission to their destination (for example, lack of buffer space). This counter includes datagrams counted in Datagrams Forwarded/sec that meet this criterion.

ipV4DatagramsOutboundNoRoute.name: ipV4DatagramsOutboundNoRoute
ipV4DatagramsOutboundNoRoute.description: Datagrams Outbound No Route is the number of IP datagrams that were discarded because no route could be found to transmit them to their destination. This counter includes any packets counted in Datagrams Forwarded/sec that meet this `no route' criterion.

ipV4DatagramsRcvdAddressErrors.name: ipV4DatagramsRcvdAddressErrors
ipV4DatagramsRcvdAddressErrors.description: Datagrams Received Address Errors is the number of input datagrams that were discarded because the IP address in their IP header destination field was not valid for the computer. This count includes invalid addresses (for example, 0.0. 0.0) and addresses of unsupported Classes (for example, Class E). For entities that are not IP gateways and do not forward datagrams, this counter includes datagrams that were discarded because the destination address was not a local address.

ipV4DatagramsRcvdDeliveredPerSec.name: ipV4DatagramsRcvdDeliveredPerSec
ipV4DatagramsRcvdDeliveredPerSec.description: Datagrams Received Delivered/sec is the rate, in incidents per second, at which input datagrams were successfully delivered to IP user-protocols, including Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP).

ipV4DatagramsRcvdDiscarded.name: ipV4DatagramsRcvdDiscarded
ipV4DatagramsRcvdDiscarded.description: Datagrams Received Discarded is the number of input IP datagrams that were discarded even though problems prevented their continued processing (for example, lack of buffer space). This counter does not include any datagrams discarded while awaiting re-assembly.

ipV4DatagramsRcvdHeaderErrors.name: ipV4DatagramsRcvdHeaderErrors
ipV4DatagramsRcvdHeaderErrors.description: Datagrams Received Header Errors is the number of input datagrams that were discarded due to errors in the IP headers, including bad checksums, version number mismatch, other format errors, time-to-live exceeded, errors discovered in processing their IP options, etc.

ipV4DatagramsRcvdUnknownProtocol.name: ipV4DatagramsRcvdUnknownProtocol
ipV4DatagramsRcvdUnknownProtocol.description: Datagrams Received Unknown Protocol is the number of locally-addressed datagrams that were successfully received but were discarded because of an unknown or unsupported protocol.

ipV4DatagramsRcvdPerSec.name: ipV4DatagramsRcvdPerSec
ipV4DatagramsRcvdPerSec.description: Datagrams Received/sec is the rate, in incidents per second, at which IP datagrams are received from the interfaces, including those in error. Datagrams Received/sec is a subset of Datagrams/sec.

ipV4DatagramsSentPerSec.name: ipV4DatagramsSentPerSec
ipV4DatagramsSentPerSec.description: Datagrams Sent/sec is the rate, in incidents per second, at which IP datagrams were supplied for transmission by local IP user-protocols (including ICMP). This counter does not include any datagrams counted in Datagrams Forwarded/sec. Datagrams Sent/sec is a subset of Datagrams/sec.

ipV4DatagramsPerSec.name: ipV4DatagramsPerSec
ipV4DatagramsPerSec.description: Datagrams/sec is the rate, in incidents per second, at which IP datagrams were received from or sent to the interfaces, including those in error. Forwarded datagrams are not included in this rate.

ipV4FragmentReassemblyFailures.name: ipV4FragmentReassemblyFailures
ipV4FragmentReassemblyFailures.description: Fragment Re-assembly Failures is the number of failures detected by the IP reassembly algorithm, such as time outs, errors, etc. This is not necessarily a count of discarded IP fragments since some algorithms (notably RFC 815) lose track of the number of fragments by combining them as they are received.

ipV4FragmentationFailures.name: ipV4FragmentationFailures
ipV4FragmentationFailures.description: Fragmentation Failures is the number of IP datagrams that were discarded because they needed to be fragmented at but could not be (for example, because the `Don't Fragment' flag was set).

ipV4FragmentedDatagramsPerSec.name: ipV4FragmentedDatagramsPerSec
ipV4FragmentedDatagramsPerSec.description: Fragmented Datagrams/sec is the rate, in incidents per second, at which datagrams are successfully fragmented.

ipV4FragmentsCreatedPerSec.name: ipV4FragmentsCreatedPerSec
ipV4FragmentsCreatedPerSec.description: Fragments Created/sec is the rate, in incidents per second, at which IP datagram fragments were generated as a result of fragmentation.

ipV4FragmentsReassembledPerSec.name: ipV4FragmentsReassembledPerSec
ipV4FragmentsReassembledPerSec.description: Fragments Re-assembled/sec is the rate, in incidents per second, at which IP fragments were successfully reassembled.

ipV4FragmentsRcvdPerSec.name: ipV4FragmentsRcvdPerSec
ipV4FragmentsRcvdPerSec.description: Fragments Received/sec is the rate, in incidents per second, at which IP fragments that need to be reassembled at this entity are received.

ipV6DatagramsForwardedPerSec.name: ipV6DatagramsForwardedPerSec
ipV6DatagramsForwardedPerSec.description: Datagrams Forwarded/sec is the rate, in incidents per second, at which attemps were made to find routes to forward input datagrams their final destination, because the local server was not the final IP destination. In servers that do not act as IP Gateways, this rate includes only packets that were source-routed via this entity, where the source-route option processing was successful.

ipV6DatagramsOutboundDiscarded.name: ipV6DatagramsOutboundDiscarded
ipV6DatagramsOutboundDiscarded.description: Datagrams Outbound Discarded is the number of output IP datagrams that were discarded even though no problems were encountered to prevent their transmission to their destination (for example, lack of buffer space). This counter includes datagrams counted in Datagrams Forwarded/sec that meet this criterion.

ipV6DatagramsOutboundNoRoute.name: ipV6DatagramsOutboundNoRoute
ipV6DatagramsOutboundNoRoute.description: Datagrams Outbound No Route is the number of IP datagrams that were discarded because no route could be found to transmit them to their destination. This counter includes any packets counted in Datagrams Forwarded/sec that meet this `no route' criterion.

ipV6DatagramsRcvdAddressErrors.name: ipV6DatagramsRcvdAddressErrors
ipV6DatagramsRcvdAddressErrors.description: Datagrams Received Address Errors is the number of input datagrams that were discarded because the IP address in their IP header destination field was not valid for the computer. This count includes invalid addresses (for example, 0.0. 0.0) and addresses of unsupported Classes (for example, Class E). For entities that are not IP gateways and do not forward datagrams, this counter includes datagrams that were discarded because the destination address was not a local address.

ipV6DatagramsRcvdDeliveredPerSec.name: ipV6DatagramsRcvdDeliveredPerSec
ipV6DatagramsRcvdDeliveredPerSec.description: Datagrams Received Delivered/sec is the rate, in incidents per second, at which input datagrams were successfully delivered to IP user-protocols, including Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP).

ipV6DatagramsRcvdDiscarded.name: ipV6DatagramsRcvdDiscarded
ipV6DatagramsRcvdDiscarded.description: Datagrams Received Discarded is the number of input IP datagrams that were discarded even though problems prevented their continued processing (for example, lack of buffer space). This counter does not include any datagrams discarded while awaiting re-assembly.

ipV6DatagramsRcvdHeaderErrors.name: ipV6DatagramsRcvdHeaderErrors
ipV6DatagramsRcvdHeaderErrors.description: Datagrams Received Header Errors is the number of input datagrams that were discarded due to errors in the IP headers, including bad checksums, version number mismatch, other format errors, time-to-live exceeded, errors discovered in processing their IP options, etc.

ipV6DatagramsRcvdUnknownProtocol.name: ipV6DatagramsRcvdUnknownProtocol
ipV6DatagramsRcvdUnknownProtocol.description: Datagrams Received Unknown Protocol is the number of locally-addressed datagrams that were successfully received but were discarded because of an unknown or unsupported protocol.

ipV6DatagramsRcvdPerSec.name: ipV6DatagramsRcvdPerSec
ipV6DatagramsRcvdPerSec.description: Datagrams Received/sec is the rate, in incidents per second, at which IP datagrams are received from the interfaces, including those in error. Datagrams Received/sec is a subset of Datagrams/sec.

ipV6DatagramsSentPerSec.name: ipV6DatagramsSentPerSec
ipV6DatagramsSentPerSec.description: Datagrams Sent/sec is the rate, in incidents per second, at which IP datagrams were supplied for transmission by local IP user-protocols (including ICMP). This counter does not include any datagrams counted in Datagrams Forwarded/sec. Datagrams Sent/sec is a subset of Datagrams/sec.

ipV6DatagramsPerSec.name: ipV6DatagramsPerSec
ipV6DatagramsPerSec.description: Datagrams/sec is the rate, in incidents per second, at which IP datagrams were received from or sent to the interfaces, including those in error. Forwarded datagrams are not included in this rate.

ipV6FragmentReassemblyFailures.name: ipV6FragmentReassemblyFailures
ipV6FragmentReassemblyFailures.description: Fragment Re-assembly Failures is the number of failures detected by the IP reassembly algorithm, such as time outs, errors, etc. This is not necessarily a count of discarded IP fragments since some algorithms (notably RFC 815) lose track of the number of fragments by combining them as they are received.

ipV6FragmentationFailures.name: ipV6FragmentationFailures
ipV6FragmentationFailures.description: Fragmentation Failures is the number of IP datagrams that were discarded because they needed to be fragmented at but could not be (for example, because the `Don't Fragment' flag was set).

ipV6FragmentedDatagramsPerSec.name: ipV6FragmentedDatagramsPerSec
ipV6FragmentedDatagramsPerSec.description: Fragmented Datagrams/sec is the rate, in incidents per second, at which datagrams are successfully fragmented.

ipV6FragmentsCreatedPerSec.name: ipV6FragmentsCreatedPerSec
ipV6FragmentsCreatedPerSec.description: Fragments Created/sec is the rate, in incidents per second, at which IP datagram fragments were generated as a result of fragmentation.

ipV6FragmentsReassembledPerSec.name: ipV6FragmentsReassembledPerSec
ipV6FragmentsReassembledPerSec.description: Fragments Re-assembled/sec is the rate, in incidents per second, at which IP fragments were successfully reassembled.

ipV6FragmentsRcvdPerSec.name: ipV6FragmentsRcvdPerSec
ipV6FragmentsRcvdPerSec.description: Fragments Received/sec is the rate, in incidents per second, at which IP fragments that need to be reassembled at this entity are received.

is4dActiveSecurityAssociations.name: is4dActiveSecurityAssociations
is4dActiveSecurityAssociations.description: The number of active IPSec quick mode security associations.

is4dOffloadedSecurityAssociation.name: is4dOffloadedSecurityAssociation
is4dOffloadedSecurityAssociation.description: The number of active IPSec quick mode security associations offloaded to hardware. Certain network adapters can accelerate IPSec processing by performing hardware offload of IPSec cryptographic functions.

is4dPendingKeyExchangeOperations.name: is4dPendingKeyExchangeOperations
is4dPendingKeyExchangeOperations.description: The number of IPSec key exchange operations that are in progress but are not yet completed.

is4dTotalBadSPIPackets.name: is4dTotalBadSPIPackets
is4dTotalBadSPIPackets.description: The total number of packets for which the Security Parameters Index (SPI) was incorrect since the computer was last started. A large number of packets with bad SPIs within a short amount of time might indicate a packet spoofing attack.

is4dTotalBytesReceivedInTunnels.name: is4dTotalBytesReceivedInTunnels
is4dTotalBytesReceivedInTunnels.description: The total number of bytes received using IPSec tunnel mode since the computer was last started.

is4dTotalBytesSentInTunnels.name: is4dTotalBytesSentInTunnels
is4dTotalBytesSentInTunnels.description: The total number of bytes sent using IPSec tunnel mode since the computer was last started.

is4dTotalOffloadedBytesReceived.name: is4dTotalOffloadedBytesReceived
is4dTotalOffloadedBytesReceived.description: The total number of bytes received using IPSec hardware offload since the computer was last started. Certain network adapters can accelerate IPSec processing by performing hardware offload of IPSec cryptographic functions.

is4dTotalOffloadedBytesSent.name: is4dTotalOffloadedBytesSent
is4dTotalOffloadedBytesSent.description: The total number of bytes sent using IPSec hardware offload since the computer was last started. Certain network adapters can accelerate IPSec processing by performing hardware offload of IPSec cryptographic functions.

is4dTotalPktsFailReplayDetection.name: is4dTotalPktsFailReplayDetection
is4dTotalPktsFailReplayDetection.description: The total number of packets that contained an invalid sequence number since the computer was last started. Increases in this counter might indicate a network problem or replay attack.

is4dTotalPktsNotAuthenticated.name: is4dTotalPktsNotAuthenticated
is4dTotalPktsNotAuthenticated.description: The total number of packets for which data could not be verified (for which the integrity hash verification failed) since the computer was last started. Increases in this counter might indicate an IPSec packet spoofing or modification attack, or packet corruption by network devices.

is4dTotalPktsNotDecrypted.name: is4dTotalPktsNotDecrypted
is4dTotalPktsNotDecrypted.description: The total number of packets that could not be decrypted since the computer was last started. A packet might not be decrypted if it fails a validation check.

is4dTotalSARekeys.name: is4dTotalSARekeys
is4dTotalSARekeys.description: The total number of successful rekey operations for IPSec quick mode security associations since the computer was last started.

is4dTotalTransportBytesReceived.name: is4dTotalTransportBytesReceived
is4dTotalTransportBytesReceived.description: The total number of bytes received using IPSec transport mode since the computer was last started.

is4dTotalTransportBytesSent.name: is4dTotalTransportBytesSent
is4dTotalTransportBytesSent.description: The total number of bytes sent using IPSec transport mode since the computer was last started.

is4iAcquireHeapSize.name: is4iAcquireHeapSize
is4iAcquireHeapSize.description: The number of entries in the acquire heap. The acquire heap stores successful acquires. Acquires are outbound requests to establish security associations between IPSec peers.

is4iMainModeSAListEntries.name: is4iMainModeSAListEntries
is4iMainModeSAListEntries.description: The number of main mode state entries. This counter includes successfully negotiated main modes, main mode negotiations in progress, and main mode negotiations that failed or expired and have not yet been deleted.

is4iQuickModeSAListEntries.name: is4iQuickModeSAListEntries
is4iQuickModeSAListEntries.description: The number of quick mode negotiations that are in progress.

is4iReceiveHeapSize.name: is4iReceiveHeapSize
is4iReceiveHeapSize.description: The number of entries in the Internet Key Exchange (IKE) receive buffers. The receive buffers are used to store incoming IKE messages.

is4iTotalAuthenticationFailures.name: is4iTotalAuthenticationFailures
is4iTotalAuthenticationFailures.description: The total number of identity authentication (Kerberos, certificate, and preshared key) failures that occurred during main mode negotiation since the IPSec service was last started.

is4iTotalMainModeSAs.name: is4iTotalMainModeSAs
is4iTotalMainModeSAs.description: The total number of successful security associations created during main mode negotiations since the IPSec service was last started.

is4iTotalNegotiationFailures.name: is4iTotalNegotiationFailures
is4iTotalNegotiationFailures.description: The total number of negotiation failures that occurred during main mode or quick mode negotiation since the IPSec service was last started.

is4iTotalQuickModeSAs.name: is4iTotalQuickModeSAs
is4iTotalQuickModeSAs.description: The total number of successful security associations created during quick mode negotiations since the IPSec service was last started.

is4iTotalSoftAssociations.name: is4iTotalSoftAssociations
is4iTotalSoftAssociations.description: The total number of security associations (SAs) formed with computers that did not respond to main mode negotiation attempts (though IPSec policy allowed communications) since the IPSec service was last started. Packets that match soft SAs are not secured by IPSec.

jobObjectTable.name: jobObjectTable
jobObjectTable.description: The Job performance object reports the accounting and processor usage data collected by each active job object. A job object provides a means of managing groups of processes with respect to their processor usage and other factors. For more information about creating and managing job objects, see the Platform SDK link on the Web Resources page at http://windows.microsoft.com/windows2000/reskit /webresources.

jobObjectEntry.name: jobObjectEntry
jobObjectEntry.description: Performance information for one particular instance of 'Job Object' object.

joCurrentPercentKernelModeTime.name: joCurrentPercentKernelModeTime
joCurrentPercentKernelModeTime.description: Current % Kernel mode Time shows the percentage of the sample interval that the processes in the Job object spent executing code in kernel or privileged mode.

joCurrentPercentProcessorTime.name: joCurrentPercentProcessorTime
joCurrentPercentProcessorTime.description: Current % Processor Time shows the percentage of the sample interval that the processes in the Job object spent executing code.

joCurrentPercentUserModeTime.name: joCurrentPercentUserModeTime
joCurrentPercentUserModeTime.description: Current % User mode Time shows the percentage of the sample interval that the processes in the Job object spent executing code in user mode.

joPagesPerSec.name: joPagesPerSec
joPagesPerSec.description: Pages/Sec shows the page fault rate of all the processes in the Job object.

joProcessCountActive.name: joProcessCountActive
joProcessCountActive.description: Process Count - Active shows the number of processes that are currently associated with the Job object.

joProcessCountTerminated.name: joProcessCountTerminated
joProcessCountTerminated.description: Process Count - Terminated shows the number of processes that have been terminated because of a limit violation.

joProcessCountTotal.name: joProcessCountTotal
joProcessCountTotal.description: Process Count - Total shows the number of processes, both active and terminated, that are or have been associated with the Job object.

joThisPeriodMSecKernelMode.name: joThisPeriodMSecKernelMode
joThisPeriodMSecKernelMode.description: This Period mSec - Kernel mode shows the time, in milliseconds, of kernel mode processor time used by all the processes in the Job object, including those that have terminated or that are no longer associated with the Job object, since a time limit on the Job was established.

joThisPeriodMSecProcessor.name: joThisPeriodMSecProcessor
joThisPeriodMSecProcessor.description: This Period mSec - Processor shows the time, in milliseconds, of processor time used by all the processes in the Job object, including those that have terminated or that are no longer associated with the Job object, since a time limit on the Job was established.

joThisPeriodMSecUserMode.name: joThisPeriodMSecUserMode
joThisPeriodMSecUserMode.description: This Period mSec - User mode shows the time, in milliseconds, of user mode processor time used by all the processes in the Job object, including those that have terminated or that are no longer associated with the Job object, since a time limit on the Job was established.

joTotalMSecKernelMode.name: joTotalMSecKernelMode
joTotalMSecKernelMode.description: Total mSec - Kernel mode shows the time, in milliseconds, of kernel mode processor time used by all the processes in the Job object, including those that have terminated or that are no longer associated with the Job object, since the Job object was created.

joTotalMSecProcessor.name: joTotalMSecProcessor
joTotalMSecProcessor.description: Total mSec - Processor shows the time, in milliseconds, of processor time used by all the processes in the Job object, including those that have terminated or that are no longer associated with the Job object, since the Job object was created.

joTotalMSecUserMode.name: joTotalMSecUserMode
joTotalMSecUserMode.description: Total mSec - User mode shows the time, in milliseconds, of user mode processor time used by all the processes in the Job object, including those that have terminated or that are no longer associated with the Job object, since the Job object was created.

jobObjectDetailsTable.name: jobObjectDetailsTable
jobObjectDetailsTable.description: The Job Object Details performance object counters show detailed performance information about the active processes that make up a job object.

jobObjectDetailsEntry.name: jobObjectDetailsEntry
jobObjectDetailsEntry.description: Performance information for one particular instance of 'Job Object Details' object.

jodPercentPrivilegedTime.name: jodPercentPrivilegedTime
jodPercentPrivilegedTime.description: % Privileged Time is the percentage of elapsed time that the process threads spent executing code in privileged mode. When a Windows system service is called, the service will often run in privileged mode to gain access to system-private data. Such data is protected from access by threads executing in user mode. Calls to the system can be explicit or implicit, such as page faults or interrupts. Unlike some early operating systems, Windows uses process boundaries for subsystem protection in addition to the traditional protection of user and privileged modes. Some work done by Windows on behalf of the application might appear in other subsystem processes in addition to the privileged time in the process.

jodPercentProcessorTime.name: jodPercentProcessorTime
jodPercentProcessorTime.description: % Processor Time is the percentage of elapsed time that all of process threads used the processor to execution instructions. An instruction is the basic unit of execution in a computer, a thread is the object that executes instructions, and a process is the object created when a program is run. Code executed to handle some hardware interrupts and trap conditions are included in this count.

jodPercentUserTime.name: jodPercentUserTime
jodPercentUserTime.description: % User Time is the percentage of elapsed time that the process threads spent executing code in user mode. Applications, environment subsystems, and integral subsystems execute in user mode. Code executing in user mode cannot damage the integrity of the Windows executive, kernel, and device drivers. Unlike some early operating systems, Windows uses process boundaries for subsystem protection in addition to the traditional protection of user and privileged modes. Some work done by Windows on behalf of the application might appear in other subsystem processes in addition to the privileged time in the process.

jodCreatingProcessID.name: jodCreatingProcessID
jodCreatingProcessID.description: The Creating Process ID value is the Process ID of the process that created the process. The creating process may have terminated, so this value may no longer identify a running process.

jodElapsedTime.name: jodElapsedTime
jodElapsedTime.description: The total elapsed time, in seconds, that this process has been running.

jodHandleCount.name: jodHandleCount
jodHandleCount.description: The total number of handles currently open by this process. This number is equal to the sum of the handles currently open by each thread in this process.

jodIDProcess.name: jodIDProcess
jodIDProcess.description: ID Process is the unique identifier of this process. ID Process numbers are reused, so they only identify a process for the lifetime of that process.

jodIODataBytesPerSec.name: jodIODataBytesPerSec
jodIODataBytesPerSec.description: The rate at which the process is reading and writing bytes in I/O operations. This counter counts all I/O activity generated by the process to include file, network and device I/Os.

jodIODataOperationsPerSec.name: jodIODataOperationsPerSec
jodIODataOperationsPerSec.description: The rate at which the process is issuing read and write I/O operations. This counter counts all I/O activity generated by the process to include file, network and device I/Os.

jodIOOtherBytesPerSec.name: jodIOOtherBytesPerSec
jodIOOtherBytesPerSec.description: The rate at which the process is issuing bytes to I/O operations that do not involve data such as control operations. This counter counts all I/O activity generated by the process to include file, network and device I/Os.

jodIOOtherOperationsPerSec.name: jodIOOtherOperationsPerSec
jodIOOtherOperationsPerSec.description: The rate at which the process is issuing I/O operations that are neither read nor write operations (for example, a control function). This counter counts all I/O activity generated by the process to include file, network and device I/Os.

jodIOReadBytesPerSec.name: jodIOReadBytesPerSec
jodIOReadBytesPerSec.description: The rate at which the process is reading bytes from I/O operations. This counter counts all I/O activity generated by the process to include file, network and device I/Os.

jodIOReadOperationsPerSec.name: jodIOReadOperationsPerSec
jodIOReadOperationsPerSec.description: The rate at which the process is issuing read I/O operations. This counter counts all I/O activity generated by the process to include file, network and device I/Os.

jodIOWriteBytesPerSec.name: jodIOWriteBytesPerSec
jodIOWriteBytesPerSec.description: The rate at which the process is writing bytes to I/O operations. This counter counts all I/O activity generated by the process to include file, network and device I/Os.

jodIOWriteOperationsPerSec.name: jodIOWriteOperationsPerSec
jodIOWriteOperationsPerSec.description: The rate at which the process is issuing write I/O operations. This counter counts all I/O activity generated by the process to include file, network and device I/Os.

jodPageFaultsPerSec.name: jodPageFaultsPerSec
jodPageFaultsPerSec.description: Page Faults/sec is the rate at which page faults by the threads executing in this process are occurring. A page fault occurs when a thread refers to a virtual memory page that is not in its working set in main memory. This may not cause the page to be fetched from disk if it is on the standby list and hence already in main memory, or if it is in use by another process with whom the page is shared.

jodPageFileBytes.name: jodPageFileBytes
jodPageFileBytes.description: Page File Bytes is the current number of bytes that this process has used in the paging file(s). Paging files are used to store pages of memory used by the process that are not contained in other files. Paging files are shared by all processes, and the lack of space in paging files can prevent other processes from allocating memory.

jodPageFileBytesPeak.name: jodPageFileBytesPeak
jodPageFileBytesPeak.description: Page File Bytes Peak is the maximum number of bytes this process has used in the paging file(s). Paging files are used to store pages of memory used by the process that are not contained in other files. Paging files are shared by all processes, and the lack of space in paging files can prevent other processes from allocating memory.

jodPoolNonpagedBytes.name: jodPoolNonpagedBytes
jodPoolNonpagedBytes.description: Pool Nonpaged Bytes is the size, in bytes, of the nonpaged pool, an area of system memory (physical memory used by the operating system) for objects that cannot be written to disk, but must remain in physical memory as long as they are allocated. Memory\\Pool Nonpaged Bytes is calculated differently than Process\\Pool Nonpaged Bytes, so it might not equal Process\\Pool Nonpaged Bytes\\_Total. This counter displays the last observed value only; it is not an average.

jodPoolPagedBytes.name: jodPoolPagedBytes
jodPoolPagedBytes.description: Pool Paged Bytes is the size, in bytes, of the paged pool, an area of system memory (physical memory used by the operating system) for objects that can be written to disk when they are not being used. Memory\\Pool Paged Bytes is calculated differently than Process\\Pool Paged Bytes, so it might not equal Process\\Pool Paged Bytes\\_Total. This counter displays the last observed value only; it is not an average.

jodPriorityBase.name: jodPriorityBase
jodPriorityBase.description: The current base priority of this process. Threads within a process can raise and lower their own base priority relative to the process' base priority.

jodPrivateBytes.name: jodPrivateBytes
jodPrivateBytes.description: Private Bytes is the current size, in bytes, of memory that this process has allocated that cannot be shared with other processes.

jodThreadCount.name: jodThreadCount
jodThreadCount.description: The number of threads currently active in this process. An instruction is the basic unit of execution in a processor, and a thread is the object that executes instructions. Every running process has at least one thread.

jodVirtualBytes.name: jodVirtualBytes
jodVirtualBytes.description: Virtual Bytes is the current size, in bytes, of the virtual address space the process is using. Use of virtual address space does not necessarily imply corresponding use of either disk or main memory pages. Virtual space is finite, and the process can limit its ability to load libraries.

jodVirtualBytesPeak.name: jodVirtualBytesPeak
jodVirtualBytesPeak.description: Virtual Bytes Peak is the maximum size, in bytes, of virtual address space the process has used at any one time. Use of virtual address space does not necessarily imply corresponding use of either disk or main memory pages. However, virtual space is finite, and the process might limit its ability to load libraries.

jodWorkingSet.name: jodWorkingSet
jodWorkingSet.description: Working Set is the current size, in bytes, of the Working Set of this process. The Working Set is the set of memory pages touched recently by the threads in the process. If free memory in the computer is above a threshold, pages are left in the Working Set of a process even if they are not in use. When free memory falls below a threshold, pages are trimmed from Working Sets. If they are needed they will then be soft-faulted back into the Working Set before leaving main memory.

jodWorkingSetPeak.name: jodWorkingSetPeak
jodWorkingSetPeak.description: Working Set Peak is the maximum size, in bytes, of the Working Set of this process at any point in time. The Working Set is the set of memory pages touched recently by the threads in the process. If free memory in the computer is above a threshold, pages are left in the Working Set of a process even if they are not in use. When free memory falls below a threshold, pages are trimmed from Working Sets. If they are needed they will then be soft-faulted back into the Working Set before they leave main memory.

logicalDiskTable.name: logicalDiskTable
logicalDiskTable.description: The Logical Disk performance object consists of counters that monitor logical partitions of hard or fixed disk drives. System Monitor identifies logical disks by their drive letter, such as 'C.' To monitor Logical Disk object counters, you must activate them by typing the following at the command prompt: diskperf -yv

logicalDiskEntry.name: logicalDiskEntry
logicalDiskEntry.description: Performance information for one particular instance of 'LogicalDisk' object.

lDiskPercentDiskReadTime.name: lDiskPercentDiskReadTime
lDiskPercentDiskReadTime.description: % Disk Read Time is the percentage of elapsed time that the selected disk drive was busy servicing read requests.

lDiskPercentDiskTime.name: lDiskPercentDiskTime
lDiskPercentDiskTime.description: % Disk Time is the percentage of elapsed time that the selected disk drive was busy servicing read or write requests.

lDiskPercentDiskWriteTime.name: lDiskPercentDiskWriteTime
lDiskPercentDiskWriteTime.description: % Disk Write Time is the percentage of elapsed time that the selected disk drive was busy servicing write requests.

lDiskPercentFreeSpace.name: lDiskPercentFreeSpace
lDiskPercentFreeSpace.description: % Free Space is the percentage of total usable space on the selected logical disk drive that was free.

lDiskPercentIdleTime.name: lDiskPercentIdleTime
lDiskPercentIdleTime.description: % Idle Time reports the percentage of time during the sample interval that the disk was idle.

lDiskAvgDiskBytesPerRead.name: lDiskAvgDiskBytesPerRead
lDiskAvgDiskBytesPerRead.description: Avg. Disk Bytes/Read is the average number of bytes transferred from the disk during read operations.

lDiskAvgDiskBytesPerTransfer.name: lDiskAvgDiskBytesPerTransfer
lDiskAvgDiskBytesPerTransfer.description: Avg. Disk Bytes/Transfer is the average number of bytes transferred to or from the disk during write or read operations.

lDiskAvgDiskBytesPerWrite.name: lDiskAvgDiskBytesPerWrite
lDiskAvgDiskBytesPerWrite.description: Avg. Disk Bytes/Write is the average number of bytes transferred to the disk during write operations.

lDiskAvgDiskQueueLength.name: lDiskAvgDiskQueueLength
lDiskAvgDiskQueueLength.description: Avg. Disk Queue Length is the average number of both read and write requests that were queued for the selected disk during the sample interval.

lDiskAvgDiskReadQueueLength.name: lDiskAvgDiskReadQueueLength
lDiskAvgDiskReadQueueLength.description: Avg. Disk Read Queue Length is the average number of read requests that were queued for the selected disk during the sample interval.

lDiskAvgDiskWriteQueueLength.name: lDiskAvgDiskWriteQueueLength
lDiskAvgDiskWriteQueueLength.description: Avg. Disk Write Queue Length is the average number of write requests that were queued for the selected disk during the sample interval.

lDiskAvgDiskSecPerRead.name: lDiskAvgDiskSecPerRead
lDiskAvgDiskSecPerRead.description: Avg. Disk sec/Read is the average time, in seconds, of a read of data from the disk.

lDiskAvgDiskSecPerTransfer.name: lDiskAvgDiskSecPerTransfer
lDiskAvgDiskSecPerTransfer.description: Avg. Disk sec/Transfer is the time, in seconds, of the average disk transfer.

lDiskAvgDiskSecPerWrite.name: lDiskAvgDiskSecPerWrite
lDiskAvgDiskSecPerWrite.description: Avg. Disk sec/Write is the average time, in seconds, of a write of data to the disk.

lDiskCurrentDiskQueueLength.name: lDiskCurrentDiskQueueLength
lDiskCurrentDiskQueueLength.description: Current Disk Queue Length is the number of requests outstanding on the disk at the time the performance data is collected. It also includes requests in service at the time of the collection. This is a instantaneous snapshot, not an average over the time i

lDiskDiskBytesPerSec.name: lDiskDiskBytesPerSec
lDiskDiskBytesPerSec.description: Disk Bytes/sec is the rate bytes are transferred to or from the disk during write or read operations.

lDiskDiskReadBytesPerSec.name: lDiskDiskReadBytesPerSec
lDiskDiskReadBytesPerSec.description: Disk Read Bytes/sec is the rate at which bytes are transferred from the disk during read operations.

lDiskDiskReadsPerSec.name: lDiskDiskReadsPerSec
lDiskDiskReadsPerSec.description: Disk Reads/sec is the rate of read operations on the disk.

lDiskDiskTransfersPerSec.name: lDiskDiskTransfersPerSec
lDiskDiskTransfersPerSec.description: Disk Transfers/sec is the rate of read and write operations on the disk.

lDiskDiskWriteBytesPerSec.name: lDiskDiskWriteBytesPerSec
lDiskDiskWriteBytesPerSec.description: Disk Write Bytes/sec is rate at which bytes are transferred to the disk during write operations.

lDiskDiskWritesPerSec.name: lDiskDiskWritesPerSec
lDiskDiskWritesPerSec.description: Disk Writes/sec is the rate of write operations on the disk.

lDiskFreeMegabytes.name: lDiskFreeMegabytes
lDiskFreeMegabytes.description: Free Megabytes displays the unallocated space, in megabytes, on the disk drive in megabytes. One megabyte is equal to 1,048,576 bytes.

lDiskSplitIOPerSec.name: lDiskSplitIOPerSec
lDiskSplitIOPerSec.description: Split IO/Sec reports the rate at which I/Os to the disk were split into multiple I/Os. A split I/O may result from requesting data of a size that is too large to fit into a single I/O or that the disk is fragmented.

macFileServer.name: macFileServer
macFileServer.description: The MacFile Server performance object provides information about a system running File Server for Macintosh.

mfsCurrentFilesOpen.name: mfsCurrentFilesOpen
mfsCurrentFilesOpen.description: The number of internal files currently open in the MacFile server. This count does not include files opened on behalf of Macintosh clients.

mfsCurrentNonPagedMemory.name: mfsCurrentNonPagedMemory
mfsCurrentNonPagedMemory.description: The current amount of nonpaged memory resources used by the MacFile Server.

mfsCurrentPagedMemory.name: mfsCurrentPagedMemory
mfsCurrentPagedMemory.description: The current amount of paged memory resources used by the MacFile Server.

mfsCurrentQueueLength.name: mfsCurrentQueueLength
mfsCurrentQueueLength.description: The number of outstanding work items waiting to be processed.

mfsCurrentSessions.name: mfsCurrentSessions
mfsCurrentSessions.description: The number of sessions currently connected to the MacFile server. Indicates current server activity.

mfsCurrentThreads.name: mfsCurrentThreads
mfsCurrentThreads.description: The current number of threads used by MacFile server. Indicates how busy the server is.

mfsDataReadPerSec.name: mfsDataReadPerSec
mfsDataReadPerSec.description: The number of bytes read from disk per second.

mfsDataReceivedPerSec.name: mfsDataReceivedPerSec
mfsDataReceivedPerSec.description: The number of bytes received from the network per second. Indicates how busy the server is.

mfsDataTransmittedPerSec.name: mfsDataTransmittedPerSec
mfsDataTransmittedPerSec.description: The number of bytes sent on the network per second. Indicates how busy the server is.

mfsDataWrittenPerSec.name: mfsDataWrittenPerSec
mfsDataWrittenPerSec.description: The number of bytes written to disk per second.

mfsFailedLogons.name: mfsFailedLogons
mfsFailedLogons.description: The number of failed logon attempts to the MacFile server. Can indicate whether password guessing programs are being used to crack the security on the server.

mfsMaxNonPagedMemory.name: mfsMaxNonPagedMemory
mfsMaxNonPagedMemory.description: The maximum amount of nonpaged memory resources use by the MacFile Server.

mfsMaxPagedMemory.name: mfsMaxPagedMemory
mfsMaxPagedMemory.description: The maximum amount of paged memory resources used by the MacFile Server.

mfsMaximumFilesOpen.name: mfsMaximumFilesOpen
mfsMaximumFilesOpen.description: The maximum number of internal files open at one time in the MacFile server. This count does not include files opened on behalf of Macintosh clients.

mfsMaximumQueueLength.name: mfsMaximumQueueLength
mfsMaximumQueueLength.description: The maximum number of outstanding work items waiting at one time.

mfsMaximumSessions.name: mfsMaximumSessions
mfsMaximumSessions.description: The maximum number of sessions connected at one time to the MacFile server. Indicates usage level of server.

mfsMaximumThreads.name: mfsMaximumThreads
mfsMaximumThreads.description: The maximum number of threads used by MacFile server. Indicates peak usage level of server.

memory.name: memory
memory.description: The Memory performance object consists of counters that describe the behavior of physical and virtual memory on the computer. Physical memory is the amount of random-access memory (RAM) on the computer. Virtual memory consists of space in physical memory and on disk. Many of the memory counters monitor paging, which is the movement of pages of code and data between disk and physical memory. Excessive paging, a symptom of a memory shortage, can cause delays which interfere with all system processes.

memoryPercentCommittedBytesInUse.name: memoryPercentCommittedBytesInUse
memoryPercentCommittedBytesInUse.description: % Committed Bytes In Use is the ratio of Memory\\Committed Bytes to the Memory\\Commit Limit. Committed memory is the physical memory in use for which space has been reserved in the paging file should it need to be written to disk. The commit limit is determined by the size of the paging file. If the paging file is enlarged, the commit limit increases, and the ratio is reduced). This counter displays the current percentage value only; it is not an average.

memoryAvailableBytes.name: memoryAvailableBytes
memoryAvailableBytes.description: Available Bytes is the amount of physical memory, in bytes, immediately available for allocation to a process or for system use. It is equal to the sum of memory assigned to the standby (cached), free and zero page lists. For a full explanation of the memory manager, refer to MSDN and/or the System Performance and Troubleshooting Guide chapter in the Windows Server 2003 Resource Kit.

memoryAvailableKBytes.name: memoryAvailableKBytes
memoryAvailableKBytes.description: Available KBytes is the amount of physical memory, in Kilobytes, immediately available for allocation to a process or for system use. It is equal to the sum of memory assigned to the standby (cached), free and zero page lists. For a full explanation of the memory manager, refer to MSDN and/or the System Performance and Troubleshooting Guide chapter in the Windows Server 2003 Resource Kit.

memoryAvailableMBytes.name: memoryAvailableMBytes
memoryAvailableMBytes.description: Available MBytes is the amount of physical memory, in Megabytes, immediately available for allocation to a process or for system use. It is equal to the sum of memory assigned to the standby (cached), free and zero page lists. For a full explanation of the memory manager, refer to MSDN and/or the System Performance and Troubleshooting Guide chapter in the Windows Server 2003 Resource Kit.

memoryCacheBytes.name: memoryCacheBytes
memoryCacheBytes.description: Cache Bytes is the sum of the Memory\\System Cache Resident Bytes, Memory\\System Driver Resident Bytes, Memory\\System Code Resident Bytes, and Memory\\Pool Paged Resident Bytes counters. This counter displays the last observed value only; it is not an average.

memoryCacheBytesPeak.name: memoryCacheBytesPeak
memoryCacheBytesPeak.description: Cache Bytes Peak is the maximum number of bytes used by the file system cache since the system was last restarted. This might be larger than the current size of the cache. This counter displays the last observed value only; it is not an average.

memoryCacheFaultsPerSec.name: memoryCacheFaultsPerSec
memoryCacheFaultsPerSec.description: Cache Faults/sec is the rate at which faults occur when a page sought in the file system cache is not found and must be retrieved from elsewhere in memory (a soft fault) or from disk (a hard fault). The file system cache is an area of physical memory that stores recently used pages of data for applications. Cache activity is a reliable indicator of most application I/O operations. This counter shows the number of faults, without regard for the number of pages faulted in each operation.

memoryCommitLimit.name: memoryCommitLimit
memoryCommitLimit.description: Commit Limit is the amount of virtual memory that can be committed without having to extend the paging file(s). It is measured in bytes. Committed memory is the physical memory which has space reserved on the disk paging files. There can be one paging file on each logical drive). If the paging file(s) are be expanded, this limit increases accordingly. This counter displays the last observed value only; it is not an average.

memoryCommittedBytes.name: memoryCommittedBytes
memoryCommittedBytes.description: Committed Bytes is the amount of committed virtual memory, in bytes. Committed memory is the physical memory which has space reserved on the disk paging file(s). There can be one or more paging files on each physical drive. This counter displays the last observed value only; it is not an average.

memoryDemandZeroFaultsPerSec.name: memoryDemandZeroFaultsPerSec
memoryDemandZeroFaultsPerSec.description: Demand Zero Faults/sec is the rate at which a zeroed page is required to satisfy the fault. Zeroed pages, pages emptied of previously stored data and filled with zeros, are a security feature of Windows that prevent processes from seeing data stored by earlier processes that used the memory space. Windows maintains a list of zeroed pages to accelerate this process. This counter shows the number of faults, without regard to the number of pages retrieved to satisfy the fault. This counter displays the difference between the values observed in the last two samples, divided by the duration of the sample interval.

memoryFreeSystemPageTableEntries.name: memoryFreeSystemPageTableEntries
memoryFreeSystemPageTableEntries.description: Free System Page Table Entries is the number of page table entries not currently in used by the system. This counter displays the last observed value only; it is not an average.

memoryPageFaultsPerSec.name: memoryPageFaultsPerSec
memoryPageFaultsPerSec.description: Page Faults/sec is the average number of pages faulted per second. It is measured in number of pages faulted per second because only one page is faulted in each fault operation, hence this is also equal to the number of page fault operations. This counter includes both hard faults (those that require disk access) and soft faults (where the faulted page is found elsewhere in physical memory.) Most processors can handle large numbers of soft faults without significant consequence. However, hard faults, which require disk access, can cause significant delays.

memoryPageReadsPerSec.name: memoryPageReadsPerSec
memoryPageReadsPerSec.description: Page Reads/sec is the rate at which the disk was read to resolve hard page faults. It shows the number of reads operations, without regard to the number of pages retrieved in each operation. Hard page faults occur when a process references a page in virtual memory that is not in working set or elsewhere in physical memory, and must be retrieved from disk. This counter is a primary indicator of the kinds of faults that cause system-wide delays. It includes read operations to satisfy faults in the file system cache (usually requested by applications) and in non-cached mapped memory files. Compare the value of Memory\\Pages Reads/sec to the value of Memory\\Pages Input/sec to determine the average number of pages read during each operation.

memoryPageWritesPerSec.name: memoryPageWritesPerSec
memoryPageWritesPerSec.description: Page Writes/sec is the rate at which pages are written to disk to free up space in physical memory. Pages are written to disk only if they are changed while in physical memory, so they are likely to hold data, not code. This counter shows write operations, without regard to the number of pages written in each operation. This counter displays the difference between the values observed in the last two samples, divided by the duration of the sample interval.

memoryPagesInputPerSec.name: memoryPagesInputPerSec
memoryPagesInputPerSec.description: Pages Input/sec is the rate at which pages are read from disk to resolve hard page faults. Hard page faults occur when a process refers to a page in virtual memory that is not in its working set or elsewhere in physical memory, and must be retrieved from disk. When a page is faulted, the system tries to read multiple contiguous pages into memory to maximize the benefit of the read operation. Compare the value of Memory\\Pages Input/sec to the value of Memory\\Page Reads/sec to determine the average number of pages read into memory during each read operation.

memoryPagesOutputPerSec.name: memoryPagesOutputPerSec
memoryPagesOutputPerSec.description: Pages Output/sec is the rate at which pages are written to disk to free up space in physical memory. Pages are written back to disk only if they are changed in physical memory, so they are likely to hold data, not code. A high rate of pages output might indicate a memory shortage. Windows writes more pages back to disk to free up space when physical memory is in short supply. This counter shows the number of pages, and can be compared to other counts of pages, without conversion.

memoryPagesPerSec.name: memoryPagesPerSec
memoryPagesPerSec.description: Pages/sec is the rate at which pages are read from or written to disk to resolve hard page faults. This counter is a primary indicator of the kinds of faults that cause system-wide delays. It is the sum of Memory\\Pages Input/sec and Memory\\Pages Output/sec. It is counted in numbers of pages, so it can be compared to other counts of pages, such as Memory\\Page Faults/sec, without conversion. It includes pages retrieved to satisfy faults in the file system cache (usually requested by applications) non-cached mapped memory files.

memoryPoolNonpagedAllocs.name: memoryPoolNonpagedAllocs
memoryPoolNonpagedAllocs.description: Pool Nonpaged Allocs is the number of calls to allocate space in the nonpaged pool. The nonpaged pool is an area of system memory area for objects that cannot be written to disk, and must remain in physical memory as long as they are allocated. It is measured in numbers of calls to allocate space, regardless of the amount of space allocated in each call. This counter displays the last observed value only; it is not an average.

memoryPoolNonpagedBytes.name: memoryPoolNonpagedBytes
memoryPoolNonpagedBytes.description: Pool Nonpaged Bytes is the size, in bytes, of the nonpaged pool, an area of system memory (physical memory used by the operating system) for objects that cannot be written to disk, but must remain in physical memory as long as they are allocated. Memory\\Pool Nonpaged Bytes is calculated differently than Process\\Pool Nonpaged Bytes, so it might not equal Process\\Pool Nonpaged Bytes\\_Total. This counter displays the last observed value only; it is not an average.

memoryPoolPagedAllocs.name: memoryPoolPagedAllocs
memoryPoolPagedAllocs.description: Pool Paged Allocs is the number of calls to allocate space in the paged pool. The paged pool is an area of system memory (physical memory used by the operating system) for objects that can be written to disk when they are not being used. It is measured in numbers of calls to allocate space, regardless of the amount of space allocated in each call. This counter displays the last observed value only; it is not an average.

memoryPoolPagedBytes.name: memoryPoolPagedBytes
memoryPoolPagedBytes.description: Pool Paged Bytes is the size, in bytes, of the paged pool, an area of system memory (physical memory used by the operating system) for objects that can be written to disk when they are not being used. Memory\\Pool Paged Bytes is calculated differently than Process\\Pool Paged Bytes, so it might not equal Process\\Pool Paged Bytes\\_Total. This counter displays the last observed value only; it is not an average.

memoryPoolPagedResidentBytes.name: memoryPoolPagedResidentBytes
memoryPoolPagedResidentBytes.description: Pool Paged Resident Bytes is the current size, in bytes, of the paged pool. The paged pool is an area of system memory (physical memory used by the operating system) for objects that can be written to disk when they are not being used. Space used by the paged and nonpaged pools are taken from physical memory, so a pool that is too large denies memory space to processes. This counter displays the last observed value only; it is not an average.

memorySystemCacheResidentBytes.name: memorySystemCacheResidentBytes
memorySystemCacheResidentBytes.description: System Cache Resident Bytes is the size, in bytes, of the pageable operating system code in the file system cache. This value includes only current physical pages and does not include any virtual memory pages not currently resident. It does equal the System Cache value shown in Task Manager. As a result, this value may be smaller than the actual amount of virtual memory in use by the file system cache. This value is a component of Memory\\System Code Resident Bytes which represents all pageable operating system code that is currently in physical memory. This counter displays the last observed value only; it is not an average.

memorySystemCodeResidentBytes.name: memorySystemCodeResidentBytes
memorySystemCodeResidentBytes.description: System Code Resident Bytes is the size, in bytes of the operating system code currently in physical memory that can be written to disk when not in use. This value is a component of Memory\\System Code Total Bytes, which also includes operating system code on disk. Memory\\System Code Resident Bytes (and Memory\\System Code Total Bytes) does not include code that must remain in physical memory and cannot be written to disk. This counter displays the last observed value only; it is not an average.

memorySystemCodeTotalBytes.name: memorySystemCodeTotalBytes
memorySystemCodeTotalBytes.description: System Code Total Bytes is the size, in bytes, of the pageable operating system code currently in virtual memory. It is a measure of the amount of physical memory being used by the operating system that can be written to disk when not in use. This value is calculated by summing the bytes in Ntoskrnl.exe, Hal.dll, the boot drivers, and file systems loaded by Ntldr/osloader. This counter does not include code that must remain in physical memory and cannot be written to disk. This counter displays the last observed value only; it is not an average.

memorySystemDriverResidentBytes.name: memorySystemDriverResidentBytes
memorySystemDriverResidentBytes.description: System Driver Resident Bytes is the size, in bytes, of the pageable physical memory being used by device drivers. It is the working set (physical memory area) of the drivers. This value is a component of Memory\\System Driver Total Bytes, which also includes driver memory that has been written to disk. Neither Memory\\System Driver Resident Bytes nor Memory\\System Driver Total Bytes includes memory that cannot be written to disk.

memorySystemDriverTotalBytes.name: memorySystemDriverTotalBytes
memorySystemDriverTotalBytes.description: System Driver Total Bytes is the size, in bytes, of the pageable virtual memory currently being used by device drivers. Pageable memory can be written to disk when it is not being used. It includes physical memory (Memory\\System Driver Resident Bytes) and code and data paged to disk. It is a component of Memory\\System Code Total Bytes. This counter displays the last observed value only; it is not an average.

memoryTranFaultsPerSec.name: memoryTranFaultsPerSec
memoryTranFaultsPerSec.description: Transition Faults/sec is the rate at which page faults are resolved by recovering pages that were being used by another process sharing the page, or were on the modified page list or the standby list, or were being written to disk at the time of the page fault. The pages were recovered without additional disk activity. Transition faults are counted in numbers of faults; because only one page is faulted in each operation, it is also equal to the number of pages faulted.

memoryTranPagesRePurposedPerSec.name: memoryTranPagesRePurposedPerSec
memoryTranPagesRePurposedPerSec.description: Transition Pages RePurposed is the rate at which the number of transition cache pages were reused for a different purpose. These pages would have otherwise remained in the page cache to provide a (fast) soft fault (instead of retrieving it from backing store) in the event the page was accessed in the future. Note these pages can contain private or sharable memory.

memoryWriteCopiesPerSec.name: memoryWriteCopiesPerSec
memoryWriteCopiesPerSec.description: Write Copies/sec is the rate at which page faults are caused by attempts to write that have been satisfied by coping of the page from elsewhere in physical memory. This is an economical way of sharing data since pages are only copied when they are written to; otherwise, the page is shared. This counter shows the number of copies, without regard for the number of pages copied in each operation.

memoryCacheKBytes.name: memoryCacheKBytes
memoryCacheKBytes.description: Cache KiloBytes is the sum of the Memory\\System Cache Resident KiloBytes, Memory\\System Driver Resident KiloBytes, Memory\\System Code Resident KiloBytes, and Memory\\Pool Paged Resident KiloBytes counters. This counter displays the last observed value only; it is not an average.

memoryCacheKBytesPeak.name: memoryCacheKBytesPeak
memoryCacheKBytesPeak.description: Cache KiloBytes Peak is the maximum number of kilobytes used by the file system cache since the system was last restarted. This might be larger than the current size of the cache. This counter displays the last observed value only; it is not an average.

memoryCommittedKBytes.name: memoryCommittedKBytes
memoryCommittedKBytes.description: Committed KiloBytes is the amount of committed virtual memory, in kilobytes. Committed memory is the physical memory which has space reserved on the disk paging file(s). There can be one or more paging files on each physical drive. This counter displays the last observed value only; it is not an average.

memoryPoolNonpagedKBytes.name: memoryPoolNonpagedKBytes
memoryPoolNonpagedKBytes.description: Pool Nonpaged KiloBytes is the size, in kilobytes, of the nonpaged pool, an area of system memory (physical memory used by the operating system) for objects that cannot be written to disk, but must remain in physical memory as long as they are allocated. Memory\\Pool Nonpaged KiloBytes is calculated differently than Process\\Pool Nonpaged KiloBytes, so it might not equal Process\\Pool Nonpaged KiloBytes\\_Total. This counter displays the last observed value only; it is not an average.

memoryPoolPagedKBytes.description: Pool Paged KiloBytes is the size, in kilobytes, of the paged pool, an area of system memory (physical memory used by the operating system) for objects that can be written to disk when they are not being used. Memory\\Pool Paged KiloBytes is calculated differently than Process\\Pool Paged KiloBytes, so it might not equal Process\\Pool Paged KiloBytes\\_Total. This counter displays the last observed value only; it is not an average.

This counter does not include code that must remain in physical memory and cannot be written to disk. This counter displays the last observed value only; it is not an average.
