telephonyCurrentIncomingCalls.description: Current incoming calls being serviced by this computer.

telephonyCurrentOutgoingCalls.name: telephonyCurrentOutgoingCalls
telephonyCurrentOutgoingCalls.description: Current outgoing calls being serviced by this computer.

telephonyIncomingCallsPerSec.name: telephonyIncomingCallsPerSec
telephonyIncomingCallsPerSec.description: The rate of incoming calls answered by this computer.

telephonyLines.name: telephonyLines
telephonyLines.description: The number of telephone lines serviced by this computer.

telephonyOutgoingCallsPerSec.name: telephonyOutgoingCallsPerSec
telephonyOutgoingCallsPerSec.description: The rate of outgoing calls made by this computer.

telephonyTelephoneDevices.name: telephonyTelephoneDevices
telephonyTelephoneDevices.description: The number of telephone devices serviced by this computer.

tsActiveSessions.name: tsActiveSessions
tsActiveSessions.description: Number of active Terminal Services sessions.

tsInactiveSessions.name: tsInactiveSessions
tsInactiveSessions.description: Number of inactive Terminal Services sessions.

tsTotalSessions.name: tsTotalSessions
tsTotalSessions.description: Total number of Terminal Services sessions.

terminalServicesSessionTable.name: terminalServicesSessionTable
terminalServicesSessionTable.description: The Terminal Services Session object provides per-session resource statistics such as packet and frame transmission data, errors, and cache activity for Terminal Services.

terminalServicesSessionEntry.name: terminalServicesSessionEntry
terminalServicesSessionEntry.description: Performance information for one particular instance of 'Terminal Services Session' object.

tssPercentPrivilegedTime.name: tssPercentPrivilegedTime
tssPercentPrivilegedTime.description: % Privileged Time is the percentage of elapsed time that the threads of the process have spent executing code in privileged mode. When a Windows NT system service is called, the service will often run in Privileged Mode to gain access to system-private data. Such data is protected from access by threads executing in user Mode. Calls to the system can be explicit or implicit, such as page faults or interrupts. Unlike some early operating systems, Windows NT uses process boundaries for subsystem protection in addition to the traditional protection of user and privileged modes. These subsystem processes provide additional protection. Therefore, some work done by Windows NT on behalf of your application might appear in other subsystem processes in addition to the privileged time in your process.

tssPercentProcessorTime.name: tssPercentProcessorTime
tssPercentProcessorTime.description: % Processor Time is the percentage of elapsed time that all of the threads of this process used the processor to execute instructions. An instruction is the basic unit of execution in a computer, a thread is the object that executes instructions, and a process is the object created when a program is run. Code executed to handle some hardware interrupts and trap conditions are included in this count. On Multi-processor machines the maximum value of the counter is 100 % times the number of processors.

tssPercentUserTime.name: tssPercentUserTime
tssPercentUserTime.description: % User Time is the percentage of elapsed time that this process' threads have spent executing code in user mode. Applications, environment subsystems and integral subsystems execute in user mode. Code executing in user mode cannot damage the integrity of the Windows NT Executive, Kernel, and device drivers. Unlike some early operating systems, Windows NT uses process boundaries for subsystem protection in addition to the traditional protection of user and privileged modes. These subsystem processes provide additional protection. Therefore, some work done by Windows NT on behalf of your application might appear in other subsystem processes in addition to the privileged time in your process.

tssHandleCount.name: tssHandleCount
tssHandleCount.description: The total number of handles currently open by this process. This number is the sum of the handles currently open by each thread in this process.

tssInputAsyncFrameError.name: tssInputAsyncFrameError
tssInputAsyncFrameError.description: Number of input async framing errors. These can be caused by a noisy transmission line. Using a smaller packet size may help in some cases.

tssInputAsyncOverflow.name: tssInputAsyncOverflow
tssInputAsyncOverflow.description: Number of input async overflow errors. These can be caused by a lack of buffer space available on the host.

tssInputAsyncOverrun.name: tssInputAsyncOverrun
tssInputAsyncOverrun.description: Number of input async overrun errors. These can be caused by the baud rate being faster than the computer can handle, or a non-16550 serial line is used. Overruns can also occur if too many high speed serial lines are active at one time for the processor's power.

tssInputAsyncParityError.name: tssInputAsyncParityError
tssInputAsyncParityError.description: Number of input async parity errors. These can be caused by a noisy transmission line

tssInputBytes.name: tssInputBytes
tssInputBytes.description: Number of bytes input on this session that includes all protocol overhead.

tssInputCompressFlushes.name: tssInputCompressFlushes
tssInputCompressFlushes.description: Number of input compression dictionary flushes. When the data can not be compressed, the compression dictionary is flushed so that newer data has a better chance of being compressed. Some causes of data not compressing includes transferring compressed files over Client Drive Mapping.

tssInputCompressedBytes.name: tssInputCompressedBytes
tssInputCompressedBytes.description: Number of bytes input after compression. This number compared with the Total Bytes input is the compression ratio.

tssInputCompressionRatio.name: tssInputCompressionRatio
tssInputCompressionRatio.description: Compression ratio of the server input data stream.

tssInputErrors.name: tssInputErrors
tssInputErrors.description: Number of input errors of all types. Some example input errors are lost ACK's, badly formed packets, etc.

tssInputFrames.name: tssInputFrames
tssInputFrames.description: Number of frames (packets) input on this Session.

tssInputTimeouts.name: tssInputTimeouts
tssInputTimeouts.description: The total number of timeouts on the communication line as seen from the client side of the connection. These are typically the result of a noisy line. On some high latency networks, this could be the result of the protocol timeout being too short. Increasing the protocol timeout on these types of lines will improve performance by reducing needless re-transmissions.

tssInputTransportErrors.name: tssInputTransportErrors
tssInputTransportErrors.description: Number of Terminal Services transport-level errors on input.

tssInputWaitForOutBuf.name: tssInputWaitForOutBuf
tssInputWaitForOutBuf.description: The number of times that a wait for an available send buffer was done by the protocols on the client side of the connection.

tssInputWdBytes.name: tssInputWdBytes
tssInputWdBytes.description: Number of bytes input on this session after all protocol overhead has been removed.

tssInputWdFrames.name: tssInputWdFrames
tssInputWdFrames.description: The number of frames input after any additional protocol added frames have been removed.

tssOutputAsyncFrameError.name: tssOutputAsyncFrameError
tssOutputAsyncFrameError.description: Number of output async framing errors. This could be caused by a hardware or line problem.

tssOutputAsyncOverflow.name: tssOutputAsyncOverflow
tssOutputAsyncOverflow.description: Number of output async overflow errors.

tssOutputAsyncOverrun.name: tssOutputAsyncOverrun
tssOutputAsyncOverrun.description: Number of output async overrun errors.

tssOutputAsyncParityError.name: tssOutputAsyncParityError
tssOutputAsyncParityError.description: Number of output async parity errors. These can be caused by a hardware or line problem.

tssOutputBytes.name: tssOutputBytes
tssOutputBytes.description: Number of bytes output on this Session that includes all protocol overhead.

tssOutputCompressFlushes.name: tssOutputCompressFlushes
tssOutputCompressFlushes.description: Number of output compression dictionary flushes. When the data can not be compressed, the compression dictionary is flushed so that newer data has a better chance of being compressed. Some causes of data not compressing includes transfering compressed files over Client Drive Mapping.

tssOutputCompressedBytes.name: tssOutputCompressedBytes
tssOutputCompressedBytes.description: Number of bytes output after compression. This number compared with the Total Bytes output is the compression ratio.

tssOutputCompressionRatio.name: tssOutputCompressionRatio
tssOutputCompressionRatio.description: Compression ratio of the server output data stream.

tssOutputErrors.name: tssOutputErrors
tssOutputErrors.description: Number of output errors of all types. Some example output errors are lost ACK's, badly formed packets, etc.

tssOutputFrames.name: tssOutputFrames
tssOutputFrames.description: Number of frames (packets) output on this session.

tssOutputTimeouts.name: tssOutputTimeouts
tssOutputTimeouts.description: The total number of timeouts on the communication line from the host side of the connection. These are typically the result of a noisy line. On some high latency networks, this could be the result of the protocol timeout being too short. Increasing the protocol timeout on these types of lines will improve performance by reducing needless re-transmissions.

tssOutputTransportErrors.name: tssOutputTransportErrors
tssOutputTransportErrors.description: Number of Terminal Services transport-level errors on output.

tssOutputWaitForOutBuf.name: tssOutputWaitForOutBuf
tssOutputWaitForOutBuf.description: This is the number of times that a wait for an available send buffer was done by the protocol on the server side of the connection.

tssOutputWdBytes.name: tssOutputWdBytes
tssOutputWdBytes.description: Number of bytes output on this session after all protocol overhead has been removed.

tssOutputWdFrames.name: tssOutputWdFrames
tssOutputWdFrames.description: The number of frames output before any additional protocol frames have been added.

tssPageFaultsPerSec.name: tssPageFaultsPerSec
tssPageFaultsPerSec.description: Page Faults/sec is the rate Page Faults occur in the threads executing in this process. A page fault occurs when a thread refers to a virtual memory page that is not in its working set in main memory. This will not cause the page to be fetched from disk if it is on the standby list and hence already in main memory, or if it is in use by another process with whom the page is shared.

tssPageFileBytes.name: tssPageFileBytes
tssPageFileBytes.description: Page File Bytes is the current number of bytes this process has used in the paging file(s). Paging files are used to store pages of memory used by the process that are not contained in other files. Paging files are shared by all processes, and lack of space in paging files can prevent other processes from allocating memory.

tssPageFileBytesPeak.name: tssPageFileBytesPeak
tssPageFileBytesPeak.description: Page File Bytes Peak is the maximum number of bytes this process has used in the paging file(s). Paging files are used to store pages of memory used by the process that are not contained in other files. Paging files are shared by all processes, and lack of space in paging files can prevent other processes from allocating memory.

tssPoolNonpagedBytes.name: tssPoolNonpagedBytes
tssPoolNonpagedBytes.description: Pool Nonpaged Bytes is the number of bytes in the nonpaged pool, an area of system memory (physical memory used by the operating system) for objects that cannot be written to disk, but must remain in physical memory as long as they are allocated. Memory: Pool Nonpaged Bytes is calculated differently than Process: Pool Nonpaged Bytes, so it might not equal Process: Pool Nonpaged Bytes: _Total. This counter displays the last observed value only; it is not an average.

tssPoolPagedBytes.name: tssPoolPagedBytes
tssPoolPagedBytes.description: Pool Paged Bytes is the number of bytes in the paged pool, an area of system memory (physical memory used by the operating system) for objects that can be written to disk when they are not being used. Memory: Pool Paged Bytes is calculated differently than Process: Pool Paged Bytes, so it might not equal Process: Pool Paged Bytes: _Total. This counter displays the last observed value only; it is not an average.

tssPrivateBytes.name: tssPrivateBytes
tssPrivateBytes.description: Private Bytes is the current number of bytes this process has allocated that cannot be shared with other processes.

tssProtocolBitmapCacheHitRatio.name: tssProtocolBitmapCacheHitRatio
tssProtocolBitmapCacheHitRatio.description: Hit ratio in the protocol bitmap cache. A higher hit ratio means better performance since data transmissions are reduced. Low hit ratios are due to the screen updating with new information that is either not re-used, or is flushed out of the client cache.

tssProtocolBitmapCacheHits.name: tssProtocolBitmapCacheHits
tssProtocolBitmapCacheHits.description: Number of hits in the protocol bitmap cache.

tssProtocolBitmapCacheReads.name: tssProtocolBitmapCacheReads
tssProtocolBitmapCacheReads.description: Number of references to the protocol bitmap cache.

tssProtocolBrushCacheHitRatio.name: tssProtocolBrushCacheHitRatio
tssProtocolBrushCacheHitRatio.description: Hit ratio in the protocol brush cache. A higher hit ratio means better performance since data transmissions are reduced. Low hit ratios are due to the screen updating with new information that is either not re-used, or is flushed out of the client cache.

tssProtocolBrushCacheHits.name: tssProtocolBrushCacheHits
tssProtocolBrushCacheHits.description: Number of hits in the protocol brush cache.

tssProtocolBrushCacheReads.name: tssProtocolBrushCacheReads
tssProtocolBrushCacheReads.description: Number of references to the protocol brush cache.

tssProtocolGlyphCacheHitRatio.name: tssProtocolGlyphCacheHitRatio
tssProtocolGlyphCacheHitRatio.description: Hit ratio in the protocol glyph cache. A higher hit ratio means better performance since data transmissions are reduced. Low hit ratios are due to the screen updating with new information that is either not re-used, or is flushed out of the client cache.

tssProtocolGlyphCacheHits.name: tssProtocolGlyphCacheHits
tssProtocolGlyphCacheHits.description: Number of hits in the protocol glyph cache.

tssProtocolGlyphCacheReads.name: tssProtocolGlyphCacheReads
tssProtocolGlyphCacheReads.description: Number of references to the protocol glyph cache.

tssProtocolSvScrnBtmpCachHtRatio.name: tssProtocolSvScrnBtmpCachHtRatio
tssProtocolSvScrnBtmpCachHtRatio.description: Hit ratio in the protocol save screen bitmap cache. A higher hit ratio means better performance since data transmissions are reduced. Low hit ratios are due to the screen updating with new information that is either not re-used, or is flushed out of the client cache.

tssProtocolSvScrnBtmpCachHts.name: tssProtocolSvScrnBtmpCachHts
tssProtocolSvScrnBtmpCachHts.description: Number of hits in the protocol save screen bitmap cache.

tssProtocolSvScrnBtmpCachReads.name: tssProtocolSvScrnBtmpCachReads
tssProtocolSvScrnBtmpCachReads.description: Number of references to the protocol save screen bitmap cache.

tssThreadCount.name: tssThreadCount
tssThreadCount.description: The number of threads currently active in this process. An instruction is the basic unit of execution in a processor, and a thread is the object that executes instructions. Every running process has at least one thread.

tssTotalAsyncFrameError.name: tssTotalAsyncFrameError
tssTotalAsyncFrameError.description: Total number of async framing errors. These can be caused by a noisy transmission line. Using a smaller packet size may help in some cases.

tssTotalAsyncOverflow.name: tssTotalAsyncOverflow
tssTotalAsyncOverflow.description: Total number of async overflow errors. These can be caused by a lack of buffer space available on the host.

tssTotalAsyncOverrun.name: tssTotalAsyncOverrun
tssTotalAsyncOverrun.description: Total number of async overrun errors. These can be caused by the baud rate being faster than the computer can handle, or a non-16550 serial line is used. Overruns can also occur if too many high speed serial lines are active at one time for the processor's power.

tssTotalAsyncParityError.name: tssTotalAsyncParityError
tssTotalAsyncParityError.description: Total number of async parity errors. These can be caused by a noisy transmission line.

tssTotalBytes.name: tssTotalBytes
tssTotalBytes.description: Total number of bytes on this Session that includes all protocol overhead.

tssTotalCompressFlushes.name: tssTotalCompressFlushes
tssTotalCompressFlushes.description: Total number of compression dictionary flushes. When the data can not be compressed, the compression dictionary is flushed so that newer data has a better chance of being compressed. Some causes of data not compressing includes transfering compressed files over Client Drive Mapping.

tssTotalCompressedBytes.name: tssTotalCompressedBytes
tssTotalCompressedBytes.description: Total number of bytes after compression. This number compared with the total bytes is the compression ratio.

tssTotalCompressionRatio.name: tssTotalCompressionRatio
tssTotalCompressionRatio.description: Total compression ratio of the server data stream.

tssTotalErrors.name: tssTotalErrors
tssTotalErrors.description: Total number of errors of all types. Some example errors are lost ACK's, badly formed packets, etc.

tssTotalFrames.name: tssTotalFrames
tssTotalFrames.description: Total number of frames (packets) on this Session.

tssTotalProtocolCacheHitRatio.name: tssTotalProtocolCacheHitRatio
tssTotalProtocolCacheHitRatio.description: Overall hit ratio for all protocol caches.

tssTotalProtocolCacheHits.name: tssTotalProtocolCacheHits
tssTotalProtocolCacheHits.description: Total hits in all protocol caches. The protocol caches Windows objects that are likely to be re-used to avoid having to re-send them on the transmission line. Example objects are Windows icons and brushes. Hits in the cache represent objects that did not need to be re-sent.

tssTotalProtocolCacheReads.name: tssTotalProtocolCacheReads
tssTotalProtocolCacheReads.description: Total references to all protocol caches.

tssTotalTimeouts.name: tssTotalTimeouts
tssTotalTimeouts.description: The total number of timeouts on the communication line from both the host and client sides of the connection. These are typically the result of a noisy line. On some high latency networks, this could be the result of the protocol timeout being too short. Increasing the protocol timeout on these types of lines will improve performance by reducing needless re-transmissions.

tssTotalTransportErrors.name: tssTotalTransportErrors
tssTotalTransportErrors.description: Total number of Terminal Services transport-level errors.

tssTotalWaitForOutBuf.name: tssTotalWaitForOutBuf
tssTotalWaitForOutBuf.description: The number of times that a wait for an available send buffer was done by the protocols on both the server and client sides of the connection.

tssTotalWdBytes.name: tssTotalWdBytes
tssTotalWdBytes.description: Total number of bytes on this Session after all protocol overhead has been removed.

tssTotalWdFrames.name: tssTotalWdFrames
tssTotalWdFrames.description: The total number of frames input and output before any additional protocol frames have been added.

tssVirtualBytes.name: tssVirtualBytes
tssVirtualBytes.description: Virtual Bytes is the current size in bytes of the virtual address space the process is using. Use of virtual address space does not necessarily imply corresponding use of either disk or main memory pages. Virtual space is finite, and by using too much, the process can limit its ability to load libraries.

tssVirtualBytesPeak.name: tssVirtualBytesPeak
tssVirtualBytesPeak.description: Virtual Bytes Peak is the maximum number of bytes of virtual address space the process has used at any one time. Use of virtual address space does not necessarily imply corresponding use of either disk or main memory pages. Virtual space is however finite, and by using too much, the process might limit its ability to load libraries.

tssWorkingSet.name: tssWorkingSet
tssWorkingSet.description: Working Set is the current number of bytes in the Working Set of this process. The Working Set is the set of memory pages touched recently by the threads in the process. If free memory in the computer is above a threshold, pages are left in the Working Set of a process even if they are not in use. When free memory falls below a threshold, pages are trimmed from Working Sets. If they are needed they will then be soft-faulted back into the Working Set before they leave main memory.

tssWorkingSetPeak.name: tssWorkingSetPeak
tssWorkingSetPeak.description: Working Set Peak is the maximum number of bytes in the Working Set of this process at any point in time. The Working Set is the set of memory pages touched recently by the threads in the process. If free memory in the computer is above a threshold, pages are left in the Working Set of a process even if they are not in use. When free memory falls below a threshold, pages are trimmed from Working Sets. If they are needed they will then be soft-faulted back into the Working Set before they leave main memory.

threadTable.name: threadTable
threadTable.description: The Thread performance object consists of counters that measure aspects of thread behavior. A thread is the basic object that executes instructions on a processor. All running processes have at least one thread.

threadEntry.name: threadEntry
threadEntry.description: Performance information for one particular instance of 'Thread' object.

threadPercentPrivilegedTime.name: threadPercentPrivilegedTime
threadPercentPrivilegedTime.description: Privileged Time is the percentage of elapsed time that this thread has spent executing code in privileged mode. When a Windows NT system service is called, the service will often run in privileged mode in order to gain access to system-private data. Such data is protected from access by threads executing in user mode. Calls to the system can be explicit or implicit such as page faults and interrupts. Unlike some early operating systems, Windows NT uses process boundaries for subsystem protection in addition to the traditional protection of user and privileged modes. These subsystem processes provide additional protection. Therefore, some work done by Windows NT on behalf of your application might appear in other subsystem processes in addition to the privileged time in your process.

threadPercentProcessorTime.name: threadPercentProcessorTime
threadPercentProcessorTime.description: % Processor Time is the percentage of elapsed time that this thread used the processor to execute instructions. An instruction is the basic unit of execution in a processor, and a thread is the object that executes instructions. Code executed to handle some hardware interrupts and trap conditions are included in this count.

threadPercentUserTime.name: threadPercentUserTime
threadPercentUserTime.description: % User Time is the percentage of elapsed time that this thread has spent executing code in user mode. Applications, environment subsystems, and integral subsystems execute in user mode. Code executing in user mode cannot damage the integrity of the Windows NT Executive, Kernel, and device drivers. Unlike some early operating systems, Windows NT uses process boundaries for subsystem protection in addition to the traditional protection of user and privileged modes. These subsystem processes provide additional protection. Therefore, some work done by Windows NT on behalf of your application might appear in other subsystem processes in addition to the privileged time in your process.

threadContextSwitchesPerSec.name: threadContextSwitchesPerSec
threadContextSwitchesPerSec.description: Context Switches/sec is the rate of switches from one thread to another. Thread switches can occur either inside of a single process or across processes. A thread switch can be caused either by one thread asking another for information, or by a thread being preempted by another, higher priority thread becoming ready to run. Unlike some early operating systems, Windows NT uses process boundaries for subsystem protection in addition to the traditional protection of user and privileged modes. These subsystem processes provide additional protection. Therefore, some work done by Windows NT on behalf of an application appear in other subsystem processes in addition to the privileged time in the application. Switching to the subsystem process causes one Context Switch in the application thread. Switching back causes another Context Switch in the subsystem thread.

threadElapsedTime.name: threadElapsedTime
threadElapsedTime.description: The total elapsed time (in seconds) this thread has been running.

threadIDProcess.name: threadIDProcess
threadIDProcess.description: ID Process is the unique identifier of this process. ID Process numbers are reused, so they only identify a process for the lifetime of that process.

threadIDThread.name: threadIDThread
threadIDThread.description: ID Thread is the unique identifier of this thread. ID Thread numbers are reused, so they only identify a thread for the lifetime of that thread.

threadPriorityBase.name: threadPriorityBase
threadPriorityBase.description: The current base priority of this thread. The system can raise the thread's dynamic priority above the base priority if the thread is handling user input, or lower it towards the base priority if the thread becomes compute bound.

threadPriorityCurrent.name: threadPriorityCurrent
threadPriorityCurrent.description: The current dynamic priority of this thread. The system can raise the thread's dynamic priority above the base priority if the thread is handling user input, or lower it towards the base priority if the thread becomes compute bound.

threadStartAddress.name: threadStartAddress
threadStartAddress.description: Starting virtual address for this thread.

threadThreadState.name: threadThreadState
threadThreadState.description: Thread State is the current state of the thread. It is 0 for Initialized, 1 for Ready, 2 for Running, 3 for Standby, 4 for Terminated, 5 for Wait, 6 for Transition, 7 for Unknown. A Running thread is using a processor; a Standby thread is about to use one. A Ready thread wants to use a processor, but is waiting for a processor because none are free. A thread in Transition is waiting for a resource in order to execute, such as waiting for its execution stack to be paged in from disk. A Waiting thread has no use for the processor because it is waiting for a peripheral operation to complete or a resource to become free.

threadThreadWaitReason.name: threadThreadWaitReason
threadThreadWaitReason.description: Thread Wait Reason is only applicable when the thread is in the Wait state (see Thread State). It is 0 or 7 when the thread is waiting for the Executive, 1 or 8 for a Free Page, 2 or 9 for a Page In, 3 or 10 for a Pool Allocation, 4 or 11 for an Execution Delay, 5 or 12 for a Suspended condition, 6 or 13 for a User Request, 14 for an Event Pair High, 15 for an Event Pair Low, 16 for an LPC Receive, 17 for an LPC Reply, 18 for Virtual Memory, 19 for a Page Out; 20 and higher are not assigned at the time of this writing. Event Pairs are used to communicate with protected subsystems (see Context Switches).

udpV4.name: udpV4
udpV4.description: The UDP performance object consists of counters that measure the rates at which User Data Protocol (UDP) datagrams are sent and received using the UDP. It includes counters that monitor UDP errors.

udpV4DatagramsNoPortPerSec.name: udpV4DatagramsNoPortPerSec
udpV4DatagramsNoPortPerSec.description: Datagrams No Port/sec is the rate of received UDP datagrams for which there was no application at the destination port.

udpV4DatagramsReceivedErrors.name: udpV4DatagramsReceivedErrors
udpV4DatagramsReceivedErrors.description: Datagrams Received Errors is the number of received UDP datagrams that could not be delivered for reasons other than the lack of an application at the destination port.

udpV4DatagramsReceivedPerSec.name: udpV4DatagramsReceivedPerSec
udpV4DatagramsReceivedPerSec.description: Datagrams Received/sec is the rate at which UDP datagrams are delivered to UDP users.

udpV4DatagramsSentPerSec.name: udpV4DatagramsSentPerSec
udpV4DatagramsSentPerSec.description: Datagrams Sent/sec is the rate at which UDP datagrams are sent from the entity.

udpV4DatagramsPerSec.name: udpV4DatagramsPerSec
udpV4DatagramsPerSec.description: Datagrams/sec is the rate at which UDP datagrams are sent or received by the entity.

udpV6DatagramsNoPortPerSec.name: udpV6DatagramsNoPortPerSec
udpV6DatagramsNoPortPerSec.description: Datagrams No Port/sec is the rate of received UDP datagrams for which there was no application at the destination port.

udpV6DatagramsReceivedErrors.name: udpV6DatagramsReceivedErrors
udpV6DatagramsReceivedErrors.description: Datagrams Received Errors is the number of received UDP datagrams that could not be delivered for reasons other than the lack of an application at the destination port.

udpV6DatagramsReceivedPerSec.name: udpV6DatagramsReceivedPerSec
udpV6DatagramsReceivedPerSec.description: Datagrams Received/sec is the rate at which UDP datagrams are delivered to UDP users.

udpV6DatagramsSentPerSec.name: udpV6DatagramsSentPerSec
udpV6DatagramsSentPerSec.description: Datagrams Sent/sec is the rate at which UDP datagrams are sent from the entity.

udpV6DatagramsPerSec.name: udpV6DatagramsPerSec
udpV6DatagramsPerSec.description: Datagrams/sec is the rate at which UDP datagrams are sent or received by the entity.

webServiceTable.name: webServiceTable
webServiceTable.description: The Web Service object counters installed with Internet Information Service monitor file transfer rates, bandwidth usage, and connection rates. You can view performance data for all instances of this object (using the _Total instance) or for specific instances, such as the Default Web Site or Administration Web Site instances. In addition to these counters, counters supplied by the Internet Information Services Global performance object combine data for the Web service with the performance data they report for IIS as a whole. For more information, see the Internet Information Services Global object.

webServiceEntry.name: webServiceEntry
webServiceEntry.description: Performance information for one particular instance of 'Web Service' object.

wsAnonymousUsersPerSec.name: wsAnonymousUsersPerSec
wsAnonymousUsersPerSec.description: The rate users are making anonymous connections to the Web service.

wsBytesReceivedPerSec.name: wsBytesReceivedPerSec
wsBytesReceivedPerSec.description: Bytes Received/sec is the rate that data bytes are received by the Web service.

wsBytesSentPerSec.name: wsBytesSentPerSec
wsBytesSentPerSec.description: Bytes Sent/sec is the rate data bytes are being sent by the Web service.

wsBytesTotalPerSec.name: wsBytesTotalPerSec
wsBytesTotalPerSec.description: Bytes Total/sec is the sum of Bytes Sent/sec and Bytes Received/sec. This is the total rate of bytes transferred by the Web service.

wsCGIRqstsPerSec.name: wsCGIRqstsPerSec
wsCGIRqstsPerSec.description: The rate CGI requests are received by the Web service.

wsConnAtmpsPerSec.name: wsConnAtmpsPerSec
wsConnAtmpsPerSec.description: The rate that connections to the Web service are being attempted.

wsCopyRqstsPerSec.name: wsCopyRqstsPerSec
wsCopyRqstsPerSec.description: The rate HTTP requests using the COPY method are made. Copy requests are used for copying files and directories.

wsCurrentAnonymousUsers.name: wsCurrentAnonymousUsers
wsCurrentAnonymousUsers.description: Current Anonymous Users is the number of users who currently have an anonymous connection using the Web service.

wsCurrentBlkdAsyncIORqsts.name: wsCurrentBlkdAsyncIORqsts
wsCurrentBlkdAsyncIORqsts.description: Current requests temporarily blocked due to bandwidth throttling settings.

wsCurrentCALCountForSSLConns.name: wsCurrentCALCountForSSLConns
wsCurrentCALCountForSSLConns.description: This counter is no longer valid. Value will always be zero.

wsCurrentCALCountForAuthdUsers.name: wsCurrentCALCountForAuthdUsers
wsCurrentCALCountForAuthdUsers.description: This counter is no longer valid. Value will always be zero.

wsCurrentCGIRqsts.name: wsCurrentCGIRqsts
wsCurrentCGIRqsts.description: Current CGI Requests is the current number of CGI requests being simultaneously processed by the Web service.

wsCurrentConns.name: wsCurrentConns
wsCurrentConns.description: Current Connections is the current number of connections established with the Web service.

wsCurrentISAPIExtensionRqsts.name: wsCurrentISAPIExtensionRqsts
wsCurrentISAPIExtensionRqsts.description: Current ISAPI Extension Requests is the current number of ISAPI requests being simultaneously processed by the Web service.

wsCurrentNonAnonymousUsers.name: wsCurrentNonAnonymousUsers
wsCurrentNonAnonymousUsers.description: Current NonAnonymous Users is the number of users who currently have a non-anonymous connection using the Web service.

wmppCurStreamErrorRate.name: wmppCurStreamErrorRate

wmppCurStreamingHTTPPlayers.name: wmppCurStreamingHTTPPlayers
wmppCurStreamingHTTPPlayers.description: Current Streaming HTTP Players is the current number of players being streamed data using the HTTP protocol. This does not include players that are stopped or paused.

wmppCurStreamingMMSPlayers.name: wmppCurStreamingMMSPlayers

wmppCurStreamingPlayers.name: wmppCurStreamingPlayers

wmppCurStreamingRTSPPlayers.name: wmppCurStreamingRTSPPlayers

wmppPeakConnectedPlayers.name: wmppPeakConnectedPlayers

wmppPeakStreamingPlayers.name: wmppPeakStreamingPlayers

wmppTotalAdvertisements.name: wmppTotalAdvertisements

wmppTotalConnectedPlayers.name: wmppTotalConnectedPlayers

wmppTotalFileBytesRead.name: wmppTotalFileBytesRead

wmppTotalLateReads.name: wmppTotalLateReads

wmppTotalOutDistBytesSent.name: wmppTotalOutDistBytesSent
wmppTotalOutDistBytesSent.description: Total Outgoing Distribution Bytes Sent is the total number of bytes streamed to all distribution servers since the last time the counter was reset.

wmppTotalOutDistConnections.name: wmppTotalOutDistConnections
wmppTotalOutDistConnections.description: Total Outgoing Distribution Connections is the total number of distribution servers that have connected since the last time the counter was reset.

wmppTotalPlayerBytesSent.name: wmppTotalPlayerBytesSent
wmppTotalPlayerBytesSent.description: Total Player Bytes Sent is the total number of bytes streamed to all players since the last time the counter was reset.

wmppTotalStreamDenials.name: wmppTotalStreamDenials
wmppTotalStreamDenials.description: Total Stream Denials is the total number of stream denials since the last time the counter was reset. This includes both denials that occurred due to failure to be authorized or authenticated, as well as denials that occurred because limits were exceeded.

wmppTotalStreamErrors.name: wmppTotalStreamErrors
wmppTotalStreamErrors.description: Total Stream Errors is the total number of stream errors due to dropped packets since the last time the counter was reset.

wmppTotalStreamTerminations.name: wmppTotalStreamTerminations
wmppTotalStreamTerminations.description: Total Stream Terminations is the total number of streams that were terminated due to inactivity or errors since the last time the counter was reset. This includes terminations that occurred because player inactivity and timeout limits were exceeded, as well as terminations that were due to events such as late reads.

wmppTotalStreamingPlayers.name: wmppTotalStreamingPlayers
wmppTotalStreamingPlayers.description: Total Streaming Players is the total number of players that have been streamed data since the last time the counter was reset.

wmusConnectedClients.name: wmusConnectedClients
wmusConnectedClients.description: The number of clients connected to this server.

wmusConnectionRate.name: wmusConnectionRate
wmusConnectionRate.description: The rate at which clients are connecting to the server.

wmusHTTPStreams.name: wmusHTTPStreams
wmusHTTPStreams.description: The number of HTTP streams being streamed.

HTTP Streams Reading Header and HTTP Streams Reading Body equal the total number of clients connected to the server via HTTP, as indic

wmusHTTPStreamsStreamingBody.description: The number of connected clients that have read the file header and are actively streaming unicast content via HTTP. HTTP Streams Reading Body and HTTP Streams Reading Header equal the total number of clients connected to the server via HTTP, as indicated by H

wmusLateReads.name: wmusLateReads
wmusLateReads.description: The number of late read completions per second.

wmusPendingConnections.description: The number of clients attempting to connect to the server but are not yet connected. This number may be high if the server is running near maximum capacity and cannot process a large number of connection requests in a timely manner.

wmusPluginErrors.description: The number of times plugins failed to perform their function. For example, a plugin couldn't reach its user database, the plugin crashed, and so on.
